Code.CodeNotes: Use all A* codes for: specialist and general adult titles, including both highly illustrated and more text-based works. For a hobby or recreational approach. Prefer: a WF* code as the main subject and supplement with A* code(s) where appropriate. Use all A* codes with: other subject categories and qualifiers as appropriate, in particular STYLE 6*, plus PLACE 1* and TIME PERIOD 3* Qualifiers
See also: QDTN

Code.CodeDescription: Conservation, restoration and care of artworks
Code.CodeNotes: Use with: other A* codes for works about the conservation, preservation, renovation, restoration or care of any type of art, including buildings, structures, sculptures, photos, paintings, decorative arts, etc

Code.CodeDescription: Forgery, falsification and theft of artworks

Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: art sales and auctioneering, funding, patronage and sponsorship, curated sales, the Crypto art NFT market, the blockchain art market, art as a financial investment or speculation, commercial value of art, the business of art

Use for: works on the fine, visual and applied arts. Use all AF* codes with: the relevant AG* code(s), AGA for History of art and artworks, AGZ for specialist works about technique, and STYLE Qualifiers 6* as appropriate. Prefer: WF* codes as the main subject for more amateur, hobby or recreational approaches, See also: WF*

Also class here: painting or paintings in general, or in any medium with no more specific category below. Use all AFC* codes for: works about a painting or paintings, by individuals or groups, including the history of particular paintings, or a particular style of painting. Use with: STYLE 6* Qualifiers as appropriate, AGA for History of artworks, AGB for monographs of painters, AGZ for specialist works about technique, etc. Prefer: WF* codes as the main subject for more amateur, hobby or recreational approaches, See also: WF*

Code.CodeDescription: Paintings and painting in watercolours or pastels
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: gouache
Also class here: acrylic paintings and painting
Also class here: trompe l’oeil, frescos, ceiling paintings, muralism, marouflage
Also class here: ink wash, See also: AFFK

Also class here: sketches. Use all AFF* codes for: works about a drawing or drawings, by individual artists or groups, including the history of particular drawings, or a particular style or technique of drawing. Use with: STYLE 6* Qualifiers as appropriate, AGA for History of artworks, AGB for monographs of artists, AGZ for specialist works about technique. Prefer: WF* codes as the main subject for more amateur, hobby or recreational approaches, See also: WF*

Code.CodeDescription: Drawing and drawings in pencil, charcoal, crayon or pastel
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: graphite, chalk, conté

Code.CodeDescription: Drawing and drawings in pen or brush and ink
Code.CodeNotes: See also: AFCP
Also class here: etchings, silk screens, screenprints, woodcuts, lithographs, line engravings, aquatints, dry point, mezzotints, monotypes, woodblocks

Code.CodeDescription: Other graphic or visual art forms
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: collage, photomontage. Use for: general works or art forms that do not have a specific code in AFC*, AFF* or AFH*
Also class here: body piercing, body painting as art. Use with: AFKP for performance art
Use for: general works on non-graphic forms of art, or art using forms not listed below, including newer forms of media
Also class here: statues, figurines, monumental sculpture. Use for: works about three-dimensional art made in any material, and for works about the art form, or associated traditions and techniques

Also class here: petroglyphs, small-scale and monumental carvings, stone carvings, carved visual motifs, gargoyles, grotesques, chimera, mascaron, sculpted rock reliefs. Use for: both the technique and works about specific carved objects or carved designs in any material

Code.CodeDescription: Precious metal, precious stones and jewellery: artworks and design
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: goldsmithing and silversmithing, Fabergé, arts using jewels and precious gems or metals, Toreutics, etc, See also: WFJ WCP WCR WFP
Also class here: land art, site-specific art, environmental art

Code.CodeDescription: Digital, video and new media arts
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: computer, electronic, holographic, virtual, cyborg, interactive, internet, generative, telematic, sound and evolutionary arts, crypto art, video game art, software art, internet aesthetics in the arts, digital visual arts, synthetic media, AI-generated media as art, crypto arts, crypto artists, deepfakes as artworks, artificial intelligence art, algorithmic art. Use for: all works about any of the arts using digital technologies, See also: UG*

Also class here: pottery (including porcelain, bone china, earthenware, terracotta, stoneware, bisque), stained glass, enamelled or painted glass, overglaze decoration, tiles, or enamelwork as artworks, See also: WFN

Also class here: ornament, ornamental motifs, decorative details, patterns or shapes, faux painting or finishing, decorative metalwork, repoussé, chasing, embossing, metal-engraving techniques, lacquerware, wallpapers and other decorative arts. Use for: works that look at the subject from a fine arts or history of art perspective, or aimed at a more professional, technical or skilled audience, See also: WF*

Also class here: carpets, kilims, rugs, quilts, tapestries, appliqué techniques, wall-hangings, weavings, knitting, patchwork, embroidery, beadwork, quillwork, featherwork, feltwork, ribbon work, and other textiles or textile embellishments as art. Use for: works about any arts or crafts that use plant, animal or synthetic fibres to construct practical, decorative, utilitarian, ceremonial, or conceptual objects or artworks, See also: AKT WFB* WFF WFG

Code.CodeDescription: The visual, decorative or fine arts: treatments and subjects
Code.CodeNotes: Use all AG* codes for: works on the fine, visual and applied arts and for the arts of specific cultures, societies, groups, peoples, places, movements, etc. Use all AG* codes with: the relevant AB*, AF*, AG*, AJ*, AK*, AM*, AT*, AV* code(s) and also STYLE 6*, PLACE 1*, INTEREST 5* and TIME PERIOD 3* Qualifiers as appropriate

Use for: History of specific art movements, periods of arts, or the history of the arts of specific cultures, societies, groups, peoples, places, etc. Use with: other Arts codes A* and also STYLE 6*, PLACE 1*, INTEREST 5* and TIME PERIOD 3* Qualifiers as appropriate

Use for: works on both individual artists and named ateliers, collectives, studios or workshops that produced under a single artist’s name. Use with: AGC for catalogues of exhibitions dedicated to a single artist

Use for: publications that are linked to either a temporary exhibition or the catalogues of permanent collections such as art galleries, museums or individual collectors. Use with: other A* codes to indicate Art form and a PLACE 1* Qualifiers if it is the catalogue of a permanent location such as a specific gallery or museum, See also: WTHM GLZ

Code.CodeDescription: Human figures depicted in the arts
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: figure painting or drawing, illustrations of human anatomy for artists, anatomical drawing, or any art that depicts the human or parts of the human body. Use with: AGZ for techniques of drawing, life drawing techniques. Use all AGH* codes with: AF*, AJ* AK* AT* codes as appropriate

Code.CodeDescription: Portraits and self-portraiture in the arts

Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: Naked or unclothed human bodies or figures in any art form

Code.CodeDescription: Erotic art / Erotica in the arts
Code.CodeNotes: Use with: Qualifier 5X as appropriate, See also: AJCX

Code.CodeDescription: Small-scale, secular and domestic scenes in the arts
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: ‘genre’ subjects, everyday scenes and events in art

Also class here: Bird-and-flower painting, the natural world, depicted in visual, decorative or fine art forms. Use for: any depiction of nature in any artistic form or tradition. Use all AG* codes with: AKLB for illustrations, or PS* for art that has or was originally for, a scientific purpose, with AJ* codes for nature or wildlife photography, AF* codes for works about nature, the natural world in any of the art forms, with WN* codes, if appropriate, to give more detail of type of nature

Also class here: animal painters, wildlife art, birds, insects, fish in art. Use for: any depiction of fauna in any artistic form or tradition. Use with: AKLB for illustration, or PS* for art that has or was originally for, a scientific purpose, or AJ* for animal photography

Also class here: botanical illustration, plant illustrations, flower paintings. Use for: any kind of artistic, accurate representation of trees, flowers or plants depicted in any art form or tradition. Use with: PST for works about botanical art that has a scientific purpose, often works that have text about the plants, or reproductions of historic botanical works, or with AKLB for works about botanical art as examples of the art of illustration

Also class here: skyscapes, cloudscapes, riverscapes, river scenes, landscape art, veduta, cityscapes, townscapes, moonscapes, waterscapes, inscapes, Weltlandschaft (world landscape), Shan shui, natural landscapes, scenery, veduta, vistas depicted in the arts. Use for: works about types of ‘scapes’ in visual arts, or individual examples

Also class here: vanitas, nature morte, memento mori. Use for: depictions of small scale scenes of mostly inanimate objects both natural and human-made, essentially, the subject matter of a still life painting, photo, sculpture or other art form is anything that does not move or is dead

Code.CodeDescription: Human made objects depicted in the arts
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: buildings, machines, transport, cityscapes, townscapes or any object made or created by humans depicted in any art form or tradition

Also class here: sacred or ritual art, icons, votive images. Use for: works about artistic imagery using religious inspiration or motifs, artistic representation of figures, patterns, shapes, calligraphy etc for spiritual or religious purposes. Use with: QR* codes or INTEREST 5PG* or 5PB* qualifiers to denote a particular religion as appropriate and with other A* codes for works on particular types of art

Use for: works on art in any media that were planned and executed with the intention of being staged in the public realm, often outside and accessible to all, either permanent or temporary, and which may be specially commissioned for a site or unofficial or unauthorised

Also class here: guerrilla art, graffiti art, flyposting, sticker art, yarn bombing, street installations, urban styles etc. Use for: works about visual or applied art forms in urban areas, inspired by urban lifestyles or environment and in the public space

Use for: textbooks, advanced level and specialised works on techniques, perspective etc. Use with: appropriate AF* or AK* codes to indicate the art form, for example AFF for drawing techniques. Prefer: WF* codes as the main subject for more amateur, hobby or recreational approaches, See also: WFA WF*
Also class here: colour science in art. Use with: P* or T* codes for more scientific or technical works

Also class here: Photographic arts. Use all AJ* codes with: AGN* for nature and wildlife photography, AGNL for landscape photography, AKT* for fashion photography, AV* codes for photography of musicians, concerts etc, AM* codes for photography of architecture, buildings, structures, monuments, etc

Also class here: Group shows, collections from named photographic studios or specify groups of photographers who worked together. Use for: works that are or are about collections or curated selections of photos usually with a common theme or principle or representing the collection of a museum, gallery, agency or collector. Use with: AG* codes for specific treatments or subjects or other codes indicating the theme as appropriate, See also: WQP

Also class here: photographic monographs. Use for: works on both individual photographers and named studios or collectives that produced under a single name. Use with: AGC for catalogues of exhibitions dedicated to a single photographer

Use for: works that present an individual or individuals and groups through photos, including selfies and individual models, as well as works on portrait photography. Use with: AJTF for works on the practical techniques of portrait photography
Use with: Qualifier 5X as appropriate, See also: AGHX
Also class here: photographic reportage, social documentary and street photography, event and celebrity photography, photo essays, See also: DNP
Also class here: cameras, lenses, film, darkroom techniques and photo processing, retouching and digital manipulation, principles of colour, composition, etc, See also: UGP
Use for: any publication about a specific camera type or brand
Also class here: aerial, drone, studio, street, landscape, nature and wildlife, portrait, underwater photography, micro- and astrophotography techniques and guides. Use for: works on composition, etc
Also class here: greyscale monochrome, black-and-white, sepia, cyanotype, brown monochrome photography. Use with: AJTV for monochrome techniques in film / video

Also class here: flash photography, use of natural or artificial light or lighting. Use with: AJTV for lighting techniques in film / video or with AT* codes for lighting techniques or lighting design in the performing arts
See also: AFKV ATFX ATJX

Code.CodeDescription: Design, Industrial and commercial arts, illustration
Code.CodeNotes: Use all AK* codes for: works that look at the subject from a fine arts or history of art perspective, or aimed at a professional, technical or skilled audience. Use with: STYLE 6*, PLACE 1* and TIME PERIOD 3* Qualifiers as appropriate. Prefer: WF* codes as the main subject for more amateur, hobby or recreational approaches, See also: WF* WF*

Also class here: design agencies, brands, companies, firms or houses as well as named individuals. Use with: other subject codes to indicate what field of design as appropriate, e.g. AKT for fashion designers, plus AKX for historical approaches, ATT for costume designers, ATDH for set designers, ATS for makeup designers, AKC for graphic designers, etc
Also class here: typefaces, font design and fonts, sign painting, shufa, shodo, khatt and other forms of calligraphy as an art, See also: WFU
Also class here: cover design, fine binding, paper marbling, etc as arts. Use for: works on the arts of designing and creating books, See also: WFT AKLB KNTP1
Also class here: miniatures, illuminated or painted manuscripts, scrolls and codices

Also class here: book illustrations and information graphics as an art. Use for: works on illustration as an art form as well as illustration, both contemporary and historical, used for scientific, technical, narrative and other purposes, See also: AFF

Use for: Collections of art from individual or multiple illustrators, or from multiple or particular comic book or cartoon series or from a shared fictional world, universe or series. Use all AKLC* codes with: X* subject codes to indicate the form of the comic book involved, with AGZ for specialist works about the techniques of drawing comic book art or characters, with AKX for histories of comic book art. Prefer: WF* codes as the main subject for more amateur, hobby or recreational approaches or UGL for more technical digital illustration, See also: AFF WF*

Also class here: artwork from any East Asian comic book style, manga, manhwa, manhua, international styles, or from graphic novels. Use for: Collections of art from individual or multiple illustrators, or from multiple or particular series from a shared fictional world, universe or series. Use with: X* subject codes to indicate the form of the artwork involved, See also: XA* XR* AFF

Also class here: Collections of art from individual or multiple computer game designers or illustrators, or from multiple or particular video game world, universe or series. Use for: works on artistic aspects of game design, artwork, graphics, video game art, etc, See also: UGG

Also class here: universal or accessible design for products, Industrial design, designing everyday objects, Design for all, designing for accessibility, transgenerational design, usable design, inclusive design, regenerative design for products. Use for: works about product design in general, including associated trade or brand names, about design of an individual product or types of products, about functionality and safety, sustainable design of products etc. Use with: other subject codes for works on specific areas of design, See also: TBD UGC

Use for: fashion styles and trends in fashion design, general and reference works, works about specific items of clothing, illustrated works about fashion etc. Use all AKT* codes with: AKB for individual fashion designers, with AKX for history of fashion, plus STYLE 6*, PLACE 1* and TIME PERIOD 3* Qualifiers as appropriate, with AJC* for photographic collections or fashion photography, with AGZ for practical techniques for fashion students and designers. Prefer: WJF as the main subject code for works aimed at a general audience about how to dress, guides to looking stylish, practical tips etc, See also: TDPF* KNDD KNSX WJF

Also class here: millinery, cordwainer, glove making, fashion and style in bags, hats, shoes, sneakers and other accessories. Use for: works, usually illustrated, that look at aspects of the design, or the aesthetics of different accessories in fashion or costume

Also class here: folk, ethnic and traditional costume, traditional garments, national dress, traditional textiles or cloth associated with particular groups or regions, etc. Use for: works that look at costumes of the past as well as contemporary costume. Use with: PLACE 1* Qualifiers codes as appropriate
Use with: other AK* and also STYLE 6*, PLACE 1* and TIME PERIOD 3* Qualifiers as appropriate

Use all AM* codes with: STYLE 6*, PLACE 1* and TIME PERIOD 3* Qualifiers as appropriate, with TNKK or ABC for works about adaptive reuse, repurposing, restoration or conservation of buildings and structures, with other TNK* codes for topics that also concern more technical works on building and construction, from an architectural point of view, for example, TNKA for accessibility or universal and inclusive design aspects of architectural projects
Also class here: architectural monographs

Also class here: architectural drawings, sections, elevations, architectural renderings, floor plans. Use for: works that look at the subject from an architectural perspective. Use with: STYLE 6* Qualifiers as appropriate. Prefer: TN* codes for works that look at the technical nature of building and construction, See also: TN*
Use for: works that examine the individual elements of a building or structure, e.g. windows, doors, roof design, ornamentation etc

Use for: works, often highly illustrated, that look at structures specifically from the point of view of the materials they are made from, such as concrete, brick, steel, glass, wood etc. Prefer: TN* codes for more technical, structural engineering approaches, See also: TN*

Code.CodeDescription: Environmentally-friendly and sustainable architecture and design
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: low-impact, sustainable and energy-efficient or energy-neutral architecture, building and interior design and technologies, arcology, green buildings, ecodesign and environmental design, biophilic and biomimetic architecture, plans for sustainable homes, carbon-neutral building techniques, practical guides to materials, green building projects, passive building design, regenerative development and design, environmentally conscious design, eco-design, Economic and Social Sustainable Design, “green” design, etc. Use with: RNU for works about sustainability and TNK* codes for works about sustainable building and construction, 5YS* qualifiers if work falls into one of the UN SDG goals

Code.CodeDescription: Architecture: public, commercial and industrial buildings
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: agricultural, industrial, commercial and civic buildings, such as, concert halls, arenas, stadia, memorials and monuments, hospitals, lighthouses, libraries, museums, galleries, exhibition spaces, stations, airports, hotels, spas, factories, warehouses, offices, shops, stores etc. Use for: works on buildings which have a primary function other than residential or domestic, and which are usually accessible to large groups of people. Use with: AMR as appropriate, See also: JWT WTHM

Also class here: private homes, houses, apartments, flats, lofts, cottages, villas. Use for: works on house design, or about residential dwellings, both contemporary and historical, that can either be purpose built or converted structures. Use with: AMR interior design as appropriate, See also: WJK AMR

Also class here: works on cabins, huts, sheds, tree houses, follies, tiny houses, summerhouses, outhouses, boathouses etc. Use for: works about smaller domestic, but not necessarily residential, buildings and structures, often connected with leisure, holidays, recreation or pleasure

Code.CodeDescription: Architecture: palaces, stately homes and mansions

Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: architectural aspects of abbeys, cathedrals, churches, mosques, synagogues, temples and other religious buildings or structures

Use for: works that look at the subject as a decorative art, often presented in well illustrated editions and aimed at a more professional or skilled audience, including studies of interior architecture and design, lighting design, residential, commercial or other interior design specialisations. Use with: AKB for individual interior designers. Prefer: WJK as a main subject code for more amateur and domestic approaches, See also: WJK
Also class here: Landscape architects, sustainable landscape architecture, environmental designers, green space design, See also: WMD

Code.CodeDescription: City and town planning: architectural aspects
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: architectural aspects of municipal, urban or civic planning, smart cities, public spaces, the built environment, urban green spaces, parks, playgrounds, urban furniture, urban architecture, urban land management, etc, See also: RPC
Use with: STYLE 6*, PLACE 1* and TIME PERIOD 3* Qualifiers as appropriate
Use all AT* codes for: works about any aspect of the performing arts, particular performances or performers. Use all AT* codes with: STYLE 6*, PLACE 1* and TIME PERIOD 3* Qualifiers as appropriate

Use for: guides, listings or other works about any performing arts events or competition, either individual or various, such as film, theatre, comedy, television, music or dance festivals, concerts, gigs, performances, events, guides to carnivals, to costume play events, etc. Use with: other A* codes and qualifiers as appropriate, for example, with AV* codes for music festivals, or AT* for performing arts events
Also class here: media personalities, presenters. Use with: relevant AT* code to indicate whether specifically theatre, film, TV, radio etc, See also: DNBF*
Also class here: studies of the dramatic arts, dramaturgy, performance studies, theatrology, See also: DD*
Also class here: monologues, audition material, advice and techniques, voice acting, voice techniques, acting methods, acting for camera, improvisation techniques, movement techniques for actors etc

Also class here: theatre directors, directing plays, guides for putting on a play or performance, stage management, works about the organisation and coordination of a performance or theatrical production

Also class here: stagecraft, wardrobe, costume, hair and makeup, lighting design and production, scenery and props, stage, set and scenic design and creation, special effects, theatrical sound design and production
Also class here: theatre administration, being a theatre manager or producer

Use all ATF* codes for: performing arts aspects only, both for the traditional big screen and made-for-TV movies or for long-form films made for new media, including streaming, on demand or other services (but excluding episodic presentations), See also: KNTC

Use for: works on national cinemas, history or critiques of individual films, film studios, movie franchises, film reception theory, film studies, film theories. Use with: other ATF* codes for particular aspects and with qualifiers as appropriate
Use for: works about specific styles or genres of cinema. Use with: ATM* codes or other ATF* codes to describe the specific style or genre of film, as appropriate, See also: ATM*
Use for: works on short or long form documentaries, for documentary film making for the big and small screen, works on scripted, largely factual programming
Use for: works about animated films or shorts. Use with: AGZ for techniques of animation, See also: UGN
Use for: Japanese style animated films, See also: AKLC1

Code.CodeDescription: Filmmaking and production: technical and background skills
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: cinematography, editing, lighting, scenery, costume, special effects, artwork and design, makeup and hair, props, casting, See also: CBVS UG*

Use all ATJ* codes for: performing arts aspects only, both for traditional television or for new media, including streaming, on demand or other forms of consuming small screen entertainment (including episodic presentations), See also: KNTC
See also: WHG

Also class here: works on series, soap operas, plays for TV, situation comedies, made for TV shows etc both live-action and animated, fiction and non-fiction, dramas, documentaries, news and current affairs etc. Use for: works about any particular genre or style of television or small screen entertainment. Use with: ATM* codes or other AT* codes to describe the specific style or genre, as appropriate, See also: ATM*

Also class here: talent shows, reality competition or game shows, documentary-style reality shows, structured-reality shows, dating shows, improvement shows, talk shows, etc. Use for: works that examine aspects of reality TV or specific shows or types of reality TV or people who participate in reality shows, on TV, streaming services, online media, etc. Use with: DNBF for biographies of reality performers, with AV* codes for specific kinds of reality music shows, etc

Code.CodeDescription: Television production: technical and background skills
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: television camerawork, editing, lighting, scenery, costume, special effects, art and design, makeup and hair, props, casting
Use all ATL* codes for: performing arts aspects only, both for traditional radio or for new media, including streaming, on demand or other forms of consuming audio content, See also: KNT
Also class here: radio drama, audio theatre, spoken word only performances

Code.CodeDescription: Performing arts genres: film, television, radio, and theatre
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: the performing arts aspects of these genres only. Use with: other AT* codes to indicate that a work is about a particular genre of film, TV show, audio performance, stage production or with AVLM for works about musical films. Prefer: F* codes for fictionalised works in particular genres, including tie-ins, See also: ATJS ATFN

Code.CodeDescription: Performing arts genres: Action, adventure, crime and thrillers
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: works about martial arts, disaster, mysteries, suspense, gangster, heist, spy, espionage, film noir, westerns, action-based war films, shows, programmes or series

Code.CodeDescription: Performing arts genres: Comedy and humour
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: romantic comedies, romcoms, humorous infotainment. Use for: works about humour-based or light-hearted films, shows, programmes or series. Use with: ATJS for works about TV sitcoms

Also class here: romance, everyday life, or realistic drama. Use for: works about films, shows, programmes or series. Use with: ATJS for works about TV soap operas or dramatic series, or with ATN for web series or web shows

Also class here: period drama, peplums, historical biographies, historical epic films, samurai cinema, etc. Use for: works on films, shows, programmes or series where the historical period is one of the most important aspects

Code.CodeDescription: Performing arts genres: Science fiction, fantasy and horror
Performing arts genres: Superhero and comic book inspired
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: works about films, shows, programmes or series inspired by comic book characters or stories

Code.CodeDescription: Internet and digital media: arts and performance
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: all aspects of Internet as media channel, especially for material that originates online; internet celebrities, bloggers and blogging, vloggers, podcasts etc, See also: UD* KNTV KNTX
Use for: general works on techniques, studies, reference etc. Use with: JBC* for cultural studies aspects or academic works as appropriate. Use all ATQ* codes with: STYLE 6* Qualifiers as appropriate
Also class here: Latin dance
Also class here: dance troupes, dance groups, companies
Also class here: traditional dances

Use for: works about the techniques and art of directing in different types of performing arts, or works about particular directors. Use with: other AT* codes for directing in particular performing arts

Also class here: special effects makeup, SFX makeup, prosthetic makeup, hair design, professional and media makeup artistry, stage and theatrical makeup, professional works for makeup artists, cosplay makeup. Use with: other AT* codes for works for specific performance arts or with other A* codes if the work is about makeup art for fashion, photography or with 4CP* or other EDUCATIONAL 4* qualifiers for vocational titles, See also: ATDH ATFX ATJX

Also class here: designing and making costumes or props, costume play or cosplay, fancy dress. Use with: other AT* codes for works for specific performance arts or with 4CP* or other EDUCATIONAL 4* qualifiers for vocational titles, See also: ATDH ATFX ATJX

Code.CodeDescription: Performing arts: production, producing and business aspects
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: works about the techniques and practices of producing or managing in the performing arts, or the techniques and practical advice on managing the business and financial aspects of a production, including the budgeting and scheduling, the finding and development of material, fund raising, managing pre-production, post-production, marketing, distribution and other skills related to producing a performing art. Use with: other AT* codes, See also: KNT

Also class here: mime, Noh, street theatre, variety shows, music hall, cabaret, juggling, ventriloquism, pantomime, storytelling and storytellers as performers, etc. Use for: Any form of performing art, performance or related performers that does not have a more precise code
Also class here: drag artists, drag balls, drag queens, drag kings, See also: JBCC3
Also class here: clowns, funambulism, acrobatics, See also: ATXZ
Also class here: Improvisational comedy, impressionists, alternative comedy, sketch comedy, comedians
Also class here: illusions, prestidigitation, card tricks, magicians as performers, See also: QRYX2 VXWM
Use with: other AT* codes as appropriate

Code.CodeDescription: Film, television, radio and performing arts: companion works
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: non-fiction style, companion works to TV series, films, shows, franchises, etc. These are typically uncritical, such as a compendium of characters, or places, or guides to the objects, machines, vehicles, weapons, props, costumes (even if these are purely fictional) or a guide to the making of, or art of a series. Use with: other AT* codes as appropriate. Prefer: FYV or FZ for tie-in versions of novels, novelisations or novels inspired by a particular film, series, show or franchise, See also: FYV FZ YFZZ
Use all AV* codes with: STYLE 6* Qualifiers to indicate the specific style or genre of music, PLACE 1* Qualifiers if specific to a particular region and TIME PERIOD 3* Qualifiers if historical

Also class here: works on music theory, music analysis, psychology of music, theories of solfège, counterpoint, harmony, melodies, intervals, scales and modes, motifs, cadenzas, refrains, ethnomusicology, aural or ear training, etc

Also class here: Guides to both live and recorded musical performances, or buyer’s guides to musical recordings, vintage and collectable recordings, guide to vinyl records, guides to collectable album covers
Use all AVL* codes with: STYLE 6* Qualifiers to indicate the specific style or genre of music, PLACE 1* Qualifiers if specific to a particular region and TIME PERIOD 3* Qualifiers if historical

Code.CodeDescription: Art music, orchestral and formal music
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: works on classical music traditions from different cultures, such as ‘Western Classical music’, Indian Classical Music, Chamber music, concertos, symphonies, sonatas, compositions for voice and instrument such as art songs, Lieder. Use with: other AV* codes, STYLE 6* Qualifiers to indicate the specific style or genre of music, PLACE 1* Qualifiers if specific to a particular region and TIME PERIOD 3* Qualifiers if historical

Also class here: choral music of any period and tradition. music for choirs. Use with: AVLK for religious choral music, such as, Gregorian or Ambrosian chant, or other AV* codes, with STYLE 6* Qualifiers to indicate the specific style or genre of music, PLACE 1* Qualifiers if specific to a particular region and TIME PERIOD 3* Qualifiers if historical
Also class here: comic opera, operetta, Opéra comique, sainete, Singspiel, Zarzuela, etc

Also class here: spirituals, hymns, choir music, oratorios, prayer set to music, religious chanting, liturgical music, sacred or ritual dance. Use for: works on music associated with, or used in, sacred rituals or religious observance. Use with: QR* codes and 5PG* and 6* STYLE Qualifiers as appropriate
Also class here: works on musicals, film scores, musical theatre, show tunes, works on the soundtracks of music from film, TV or stage

Also class here: Jazz, Rock, Pop, Soul, Rap, Latin, Blues, Easy listening, Country, Reggae music and all their associated variations. Use for: all forms of popular music, as distinct from art music and traditional music. Use with: STYLE 6* Qualifiers to indicate the style or genre of popular music

Use with: FV as appropriate, See also: DN*

Use for: works of fiction that speculate about different realities from the actual recognisable world, or other worlds or universes, using elements of science, supernatural, paranormal, futuristic or other imaginative elements that are not part of everyday reality as a major theme of the story. Use all FD* codes with: other F* codes as appropriate, with 6JM - Indigenous Futurisms - for Indigenous speculative fiction, with other 5* INTEREST and 6* STYLE qualifiers for particular types of speculative fiction
Use for: any fiction set in an ideal or utopian society, or a dysfunctional or degraded society. Use with: FL* or other F* codes as appropriate

Also class here: Uchronia. Use for: any work of speculative fiction, set in an imagined version of our world that might have emerged had key historical events happened differently e.g. outcome of WW2, or alternate history in which one or more historical events have occurred but are resolved differently than in actual history. Use with: FLG or other FL* codes for alternate history as science fiction stories that feature the tropes of time travel between histories, the psychic awareness of the existence of an alternative universe, by the inhabitants of a given universe; and time travel that divides history into various timestreams, cross-time stories, rival parallel time worlds, with FMH codes for historical fantasy based on an alternate history or historical divergences

Use with: FL* for Black Science Fiction, or FK* or FM* or FN* codes as appropriate, with 6AR for Afrofuturism (African-American / Black American/ African diaspora speculative fiction), or with 6AS Africanfuturism (African speculative fiction) or with other subject codes or qualifiers as appropriate

Use for: fiction that explores, or is based on, some form of philosophy or system of thought, fiction where a significant portion of the content is devoted to the sort of questions normally addressed in philosophy

Use all FF* codes for: Stories about crimes, or mysteries to be solved, locked room mysteries, whodunits, heists and capers novels, crime novels, detective stories, murder mysteries, cold cases, unsolved crimes, etc. Use all FF* codes with: other codes for different types of crime fiction that do not have a unique code, for example, with PLACE 1* qualifiers for regional crime fiction, FK* for horror crime fiction, FL* for science fiction crime
Also class here: Classic whodunit stories. Use for: works of crime fiction widely regarded or presented as ‘classic’ and typically, but not necessarily, published and in print for several decades

Code.CodeDescription: Crime and mystery: private investigator / amateur detectives
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: Amateur sleuths, religious sleuths, private investigators, silver-haired sleuths, accidental detectives. Use for: stories where the main investigator is not an official police or judicial investigator
Use for: contemporary mysteries set in past times, e.g. in Victorian, Medieval, Roman period. Use with: PLACE 1* and/or TIME PERIOD 3 * Qualifiers to indicate setting as appropriate

Also class here: Cozy crime, cozies, Cottagecore crime, domestic mysteries, soft-boiled crime stories, pet mysteries, cats or dogs mysteries, cooking mysteries, academic cozies, craft or hobby mysteries, cozy silver-haired mysteries. Use for: mysteries set in rural or traditional communities featuring minimal violence and typically amateur sleuths
Also class here: Funny or comedic crime and mystery stories

Code.CodeDescription: Crime and mystery: hard-boiled crime, noir fiction
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: Roman noir, domestic noir crime stories. Use for: crime or detective stories often featuring things like gritty urban settings, bleak landscapes, or places that have been broken or distorted by crime, morally compromised or complex protagonists, dark mysteries, or a bleak, pessimistic or dark outlook on human nature, pessimistic vision of a place. Use with: PLACE 1* qualifiers to indicate setting, for example, Nordic noir crime stories set in parts of Scandinavia, Mediterranean Noir, American Hardboiled, etc, See also: FHR

Also class here: police and forensic investigation, judicial or detective investigators, undercover police operations, police stories, forensic pathologists, coroners, forensic anthropologists, crime scene investigators, covert policing, undercover cops, plainclothes detectives, etc

Code.CodeDescription: Crime and mystery: women sleuths / detectives
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: Crime or mysteries where the mystery is solved by a woman, and where the woman is the detective, investigator, police officer, or other person who investigates or solves the crime or mystery etc. Use with: other FF* codes to indicate the genre as appropriate
Use with: S* codes to indicate specific sport featured

Use all FH* codes for: conspiracy thrillers, disaster thrillers, Eco-thrillers, classic thrillers, assassination thrillers, vigilante justice thrillers, kidnapping or murder thrillers, domestic thrillers. Use all FH* codes with: other F* codes as appropriate for different types of thriller or suspense fiction that do not have a unique code, such as FL* for Sci-fi thrillers, FRM for Romantic thrillers, FK for Horror thrillers, FJM* for military thrillers, FV for historical thrillers, JBGX for thrillers about conspiracies, FXS for Social thrillers, FF* for crime thrillers

Also class here: Spy novels, stories featuring cold war spies, secret agents, undercover agents, spy agencies or intelligence agencies, counter-intelligence, state intelligence services, intelligence officers, secret services, secret police, spying or intelligence gathering, assassins or assassination plots in the world of espionage, etc

Also class here: thrillers featuring white-collar crimes, crimes of corruption, fraud or greed. Use for: thrillers in which the financial system, the world of finance and money, the financial markets, the economy, big business, world of corporations, multinational or transnational business or corporations, financial professionals, business people, corporate bosses, wealthy business families or dynasties, or similar play a major role

Also class here: Cyber thrillers. Use for: thrillers incorporating scientific, technological (including computing digital technologies, artificial intelligence), etc. elements as important parts of the narrative

Use for: thrillers that usually feature something used for medical purposes becoming a weapon or threat, such as a virus, often featuring medical practitioners as key characters, biological threats, pandemics, medical forensic practitioners, etc

Also class here: Courtroom drama thrillers, thrillers featuring lawyers, judges, prosecutors or other legal settings or roles, or politicians, the world of politics or political settings, including political plots, political assassinations, political conspiracies, political targeted killings, etc

Also class here: Occult, supernatural, mystical thrillers, archaeological thrillers. Use for: thrillers featuring traditions of ancient, secret or esoteric knowledge, such as the Holy Grail, or thrillers with occult, supernatural or mystical themes, conspiracies around secret or occult organisations or structures, etc.

Use for: thrillers based around criminal organizations, the criminal underworld, the mob, the mafia, crime syndicates, criminal gangs, contract killers, hired killers, professional gunmen, assassins, hitmen or hitwomen, criminal gangs, criminal feuds, criminal families, gangland crimes, gangsters, gritty urban crime, etc, See also: FFL

Use for: thrillers based around mass murderers, serial killers, spree killings, thrill killers, angel of mercy or angel of death type killers, etc. Use with: FK* for horror stories that include serial killers
Use for: thrillers based around potential terrorist actions, acts of terrorism, terrorist plots, political terrorism, conspiracies to commit acts of terror, anti-terror plots, etc

Also class here: Domestic thrillers. Use for: thrillers that deal with a psychological narrative, or are told from the viewpoint of psychologically stressed characters, or where the plot concentrates on investigations of the psychologies of the principal characters, thrillers that examine things like perception, reality, the mind, identity, existence or purpose, etc, See also: FXM

Use all FJ* codes for: adventure stories, stories of exploration, classic adventure or action stories. Use for: works that primarily emphasise physical, and sometimes violent, action, that often have a sense of danger and are meant to give the reader a sense of excitement or adventure, See also: FH
Also class here: wuxia, Bukyō. Use with: FM*, FV*, XQ* codes plus TIME PERIOD 3* Qualifiers as appropriate
Use for: adventure novels set in past times. Use with: PLACE 1* and/or TIME PERIOD 3* Qualifiers to indicate setting as appropriate. Prefer: specific FJM* code if applicable, See also: FJM

Code.CodeDescription: War, combat and military adventure fiction
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: Special forces stories, historical military fiction. Use for: stories that primarily emphasise the action or adventure side of war or combat. Use with: PLACE 1* and/or TIME PERIOD 3* Qualifiers to indicate setting for historical war or combat fiction. Prefer: other F* codes and TIME PERIOD 3* qualifiers for works where war or conflict is part of the background of the story or that examine the impact of war but where the primary theme could not be seen as action or adventure

Also class here: stories set during the French Revolutionary Wars, the Coalition Wars, the Peninsular Wars, the War of 1812 or any other associated war or military campaign of this period. Use with: PLACE 1* and/or TIME PERIOD 3* Qualifiers to indicate setting as appropriate
Also class here: naval and maritime fiction, nautical fiction. Use for: adventure or action stories featuring seafarers, pirates, sailors, fishermen and so on, or largely set at sea

Code.CodeDescription: Horror, ghost stories and supernatural fiction
Code.CodeNotes: Use all FK* codes for: monster literature, Lovecraftian horror, cosmic horror, Eldritch horror, psychological horror, folk horror, body horror, transformative gore, survival horror, haunted house horror, extreme horror, demonic horror or any stories that provoke or inspire feelings of dread, fear and terror, or are intended to disturb, frighten or scare, using psychological or supernatural elements, or any story that includes a ghost, or the possibility of ghosts, or a characters belief in ghosts. Use all FK* codes with: VXQ* codes if appropriate, for example with VXQG for ghost stories, VXQM2 for vampire, werewolf or shifter horror, VXQM3 for zombie horror, VXQM5 for demon horror, VXWT for stories featuring evil witches and other F* codes, for example, FU* Comedy horror, FL* for Horror Science fiction, FP for Erotic horror, FV for Historical Horror, FLQ or FDB for Post-Apocalyptic Horror, FF* or FH* for Crime horror or thrillers with a horror plot, FHX or FXM for Quiet or psychological horror, FYL for Gothic horror, or with 5* Qualifiers, for example, 5HPD for Christmas Horror, 5HRD for Winter Horror, etc, See also: FMT FHX

Code.CodeDescription: Classic horror, ghost stories and supernatural fiction
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: classic gothic horror. Use for: supernatural fiction, horror or ghost stories widely regarded or presented as ‘classic’ and typically, but not necessarily, published and in print for several decades

Code.CodeDescription: Contemporary horror, ghost stories and supernatural fiction
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: supernatural fiction, horror or ghost stories set in the present day or contemporary settings, typically first published in the last few decades

Use for: works where major themes of the story deal with the darker side of witchcraft, spiritualism, psychic phenomena, demonic possession, satanism, mysterious or secret knowledge, or other paranormal phenomenon

Use all FL* codes with: other subjects codes or qualifiers for different types of SF that do not have a unique code, for example, FU for Comical (humorous) science fiction, Sci-fi comedy, 5PS for LGBTQIA+ science fiction, 6JM for Indigenous Futurisms in SF, with 6AR for Afrofuturism (African-American / Black American / African diaspora SF), or with 6AS Africanfuturism (African) in SF, FK* for Science fiction with horror stories, See also: FD FDM
Use for: science fiction widely regarded or presented as ‘classic’ and typically, but not necessarily, published and in print for several decades

Code.CodeDescription: Science fiction: time travel / time slip
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: Chuanyue, Isekai, stories based on travelling to a past or future time via time loops, time machines, time slips, time portals, accidental time travel, alternate timestreams, time warp, temporal paradoxes, experiencing time in reverse, communication from the future, being stuck in a time-loop, stories where time is a significant element, different spacetime geometries, wormholes in spacetime, stories based on the quantum mechanics of time travel, temporal war, etc. Use with: FM* codes for time travel or time slip fantasy stories, with FDK for alternate history science fiction, featuring alternate futures, different timestreams, multiple time paths

Use for: science fiction that emphasises scientific detail and / or accuracy, or that use science that exist within the realm of scientific possibility or do not go outside the known physical laws of the universe

Use for: science fiction stories that have a more positive, lighter and more comforting, feel-good or uplifting approach to telling the story, and that tend not to create any anxiety, often featuring narratives around hope and optimism, friends or friendship, found or chosen family, communities, and where conflicts or crisis are usually resolved through communication and understanding, with the help of community and friends, often stories with elements of science fiction, but where world-building is not a major element

Also class here: dieselpunk, retrofuturism, stonepunk, atompunk, decopunk, clockpunk, steelpunk, rococopunk, silkpunk, arcanepunk. Use for: science fiction based on an alternative world where 19th century steam power has emerged as the dominant technology, or any other retrofuturistic ‘punk’ genre where a certain technology from the past has become dominant

Also class here: AI takeovers, robot uprisings, super robots, intelligent technology, genetic engineering, artificial intelligence, alternative realities. Use for: sci fi set in a very near future, from the creators point of view, and in a world that is a natural progression from their own, that often feature current technologies or technology in development and its effects upon the world, that may feature things such as advanced high tech, artificial intelligence, robots, Mecha, cyborgs, transhumanism, the technological singularity

Also class here: Nanopunk, Cyber-noir, solarpunk, techno-noir. Use for: science fiction based on marginalised or low-life characters in a highly technologically advanced society or focused on the implications of biotechnology or genetic engineering

Also class here: end of the world stories, dying earth, collapsing or collapsed civilization. Use for: stories set in worlds trying to prevent, or experiencing or that have already been affected by an apocalypse event, such as runaway climate change, an impact event, resource depletion, nuclear holocaust, pandemics, plagues, viruses, the end times, a zombie apocalypse, cybernetic revolts, technological singularity, invasion from space, dysgenics, an electromagnetic pulse (EMP), stories of groups of survivors or survival after a catastrophe or cataclysm etc. Use with: FXE for climate fiction or ecological collapse, FXV for stories of journeys through a devastated world or other codes and qualifiers as appropriate
Use for: science fiction set within the military or where organised use of weaponry is central to the plot, See also: FLS
Also class here: Galactic empires, planetary romance. Use for: science fiction set in space, usually with advanced cultures and technology
Also class here: first contact, alien invasion, human interaction with extra-terrestrial life forms, alien conspiracies
Also class here: colonisation of space, settlement of planets or moons, exploration of deep space, moon bases, generation ships, terraforming, first landings on other planets, astronauts

Use all FM* codes for: Classic fantasy, other worlds fantasy, Crossworlds fantasy, Futuristic fantasy, Portal fantasy, Parallel worlds, Quest fantasy, Literary fantasy, Hard fantasy. Use all FM* codes with: other codes for different types of fantasy that do not have a unique code, for example, with 5LKE for New Adult Fantasy, 5PX-XA-A for Arthurian fantasy, VXQM1 for dragon fantasy, 5PGM for Christian fantasy, 5PS, 5PT, 5PU or 5PV for LGBTQIA+ fantasy, FXB for coming of age fantasy, FU* for Comic fantasy, 5YH for Anthropomorphic fantasy, FDB or FLQ for dying earth or post-apocalyptic fantasy, FP for erotic fantasy or FRX for Erotic Fantasy Romance, FXP for Political fantasy, FLM for Steampunk fantasy, FJW for Weird west fantasy, FL* for Sword and planet fantasy, 6AU for Academy fantasy, etc
Use for: stories set in alternative or secondary worlds, usually with detailed world building and a complex fictional universe or shared world, and often involving large events or long quests

Also class here: Swashbuckling fantasy. Use for: works of fantasy that concentrate more on the adventures and battles of the hero or main protagonist, rather than the world building, or fantasy stories that feature a hero, anti-hero or morally grey hero going on some sort of quest or any sort of hero‘s journey in a fantasy or supernatural setting where the narrative concentrates more on the adventure rather than building the fantasy world. Use with: other FM* codes as appropriate

Also class here: Medieval, Dark Age, Classical (Greek and Roman), Arabian, Celtic, Fantasy of Manners, Mannerpunk, Flintlock, Gunpowder, Prehistoric, Gaslamp fantasy genres. Use for: fantasy that incorporates fantastic elements, such as magic or elements from myths, into recognisable historic settings, periods, cultures etc. Use with: PLACE 1* and/or TIME PERIOD 3* Qualifiers to indicate setting as appropriate

Use for: fantasy stories that have a more positive, lighter and more comforting, feel-good or uplifting approach to telling the story, and that tend not to create any anxiety, often featuring narratives around hope and optimism, friends or friendship, found or chosen family, communities, and where conflicts or crisis are usually resolved through communication and understanding, with the help of community and friends

Also class here: Magic realism. Use for: works that incorporates fantastic, magical, mythical or supernatural elements into an otherwise real-world or mundane setting, stories that have a largely realistic view of the world but with a few supernatural or magical elements, that are often used to make a point about reality. Use with: FBA or FBC for literary works that incorporate magical realism, for example, those of the kind frequently associated with literature from Latin America or other literary traditions

Also class here: Romantasy, fantasy with a romance element. Use for: fantasy stories using many of the elements and conventions of the romance genre but that remain primarily and recognisably a fantasy story, where the main plot is a fantasy story but with a strong romantic sub-plot. Use with: FRX for romantic fantasy stories with a more erotic or sexual storyline, or other FR* or FM* codes as appropriate, See also: FRV FRT
Use for: fiction featuring or where the main characters are depicted as superheroes / superheroines or superhumans

Also class here: Grimdark. Use for: fantasy stories with darker and frightening themes, often incorporating elements of horror or that have a gloomy and threatening atmosphere or a sense of horror and dread

Also class here: intrusion fantasy, mundane fantasy. Use for: fantasy set in the present day or contemporary or modern settings or set in a recognisable version of our world, but with elements of fantasy or the supernatural added in

Also class here: Elfpunk, Arcanepunk fantasy, gritty urban fantasy. Use for: fantasy works set in urban settings, often featuring plots where the real modern urban setting and the supernatural or paranormal collide or overlap, or where mythical or supernatural beings and creatures exist in recognisable urban settings. Use with: VXQ* codes as appropriate

Code.CodeDescription: Traditional or cultural fiction and true stories, tales and retellings
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: Fables. Use all FN* codes for: stories that often have a long and continuous existence through multiple generations, stories that get told and retold, traditional local folktales, tall tales, folklore, folk literature, wisdom tales, cautionary stories, teaching stories, origin tales, or any form of traditional story told or retold. Use for: modern retellings in novel form or collections of traditional tales and stories aimed primarily at adults, or works inspired by these stories, See also: DBS* QRS* JBGB YFJ YNRU

Code.CodeDescription: Fairy and Folk tales / Fairy tale retellings
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: folk and fairy tales from any culture told in a story form, or fantasy retellings of these stories, fairy tales as fiction, fairy tale fantasy. Use for: modern retellings in novel form or collections of these types of traditional stories aimed primarily at adults, or stories recognisably inspired by traditional fairy stories or that in some way draw from the characters, tropes, themes and symbolism of folklore and fairy tales and where, for example, an author might tell a new story based on a popular fairy tale or character from a classic work, or take a ‘what if’ approach or create a mashup of different genres, for example, fairy tale meets dystopian future, See also: JBGB YFJ YNXB4

Also class here: Mythological Fiction, Legend fantasy, Mythic fantasy, myths and legends from any culture told in story form, myth or legend retold as fiction, or genres such as mythpunk, godpunk, Shenmo, Gods and Demons fiction, Xianxia, Immortal heroes fiction, Arthurian fiction, Classical (Greek and Roman myths told as stories or retold). Use for: modern retellings in novel form or collections of these types of traditional stories aimed primarily at adults, or stories recognisably inspired by traditional myths or stories that draw from the characters, gods and goddesses, heroes and heroines, tropes, themes and symbolism of myths or legends and where, for example, an author might tell a new story based on a myth, or take a ‘what if’ approach or create a mashup of different genres, for example, mythology crossed with contemporary adventure story. Use with: QRS* or QRR* codes or PLACE1* qualifiers to indicate which tradition, as appropriate, See also: DBS* JBGB QRS* YFJ YNRU
Use for: stories that feature a trickster character such as a spirit, a deity, a human or an animal, or stories inspired by or retellings of stories about trickster characters from different cultures

Also class here: Erotic literature. Use for: stories aimed at adults of an erotic nature that deal explicitly with sexual relationships and themes, that are not primarily a romance story. Use with: other F* codes for genre fiction that is also erotic and with 5PRD for erotic novels about BDSM, fetish or kink sex or other erotic subcultures and INTEREST Qualifier 5X as appropriate. DO NOT USE: with FRX code, See also: FRX

Also class here: feel-good fiction, cozy / cosy fiction, up-lit, ‘slice of life’ fiction. Use for: stories set primarily in the present day or contemporary settings, dealing with realistic everyday themes or lifestyles, usually in a light-hearted, sometimes uplifting, manner, often focusing on things like the everyday trials and tribulations of the main protagonist, their friendships, their found families, relationships, ups and downs of life, their workplace or professional life, or their place of education, their day-to-day lifestyles, their social life, their emotions, or may be life affirming stories about everyday characters which champion empathy, understanding, kindness, stories of everyday joy or sadness, everyday hope and optimism, etc. Use with: other F* codes for particular genres, See also: FRB FRD

Use all FR* codes for: Love stories, classic romance, slow burn romances. Use all FR* codes with: qualifiers for particular types of romance, for example, with 5H* qualifiers for Holiday Romance, such as 5HRB for summer vacation romance or 5HPD for Christmas romance, 5PS* or other 5P* qualifiers for LGBTQIA+ romances, 5LKS for romance in later life, FL* codes for Science fiction romance, FJ* for action and adventure romance, JBSE for small town romance, 5PB-US-C for Black and African American romance, 5HKU for Romance about marriage, FYL for Gothic romance, 5LKE for New Adult romance, etc
Also class here: Rom-coms. Use for: genre romance and love stories that are also comic, humorous, light hearted or funny in their approach

Use for: romance stories where the main characters live and work in a world most readers can understand, with modern conveniences and current social mores. Use with: other FR* codes and qualifiers for particular sub-genres of contemporary romance, and with qualifiers as appropriate

Use for: romance and love stories that have a more positive, lighter and more comforting, feel-good or uplifting approach to telling the story, and that tend not to create any anxiety, often featuring narratives around hope and optimism, friends or friendship, found or chosen family, communities, and where conflicts or crisis are usually resolved through communication and understanding, with the help of community and friends

Also class here: First job romances, office romances, forbidden workplace romance, love in the workplace, professional romance, renovation romance, working from home romance, boss romance. Use for: Romance stories featuring or set in a working environment, or about a relationship with a work colleague or a romance with a person who is doing some work or working for the other person, for example, someone who is helping to renovate a building, doing some long-term construction work, the gardener, the boss, the CEO, the bodyguard, etc

Also class here: sweetheart romance. Use for: romance that does not contain any strong language or physical intimacy. Use with: FW for religious romance, faith-driven romance, or inspirational romance, and with 5PG* INTEREST Qualifiers as appropriate to indicate a wholesome romance with themes inspired by a particular spiritual belief or faith or with other FR* codes for wholesome romances that are also considered part of another genre romance, with 5PB-US-B for Amish romance, 5PGM for Christian romance, 5PGP for Muslim romance, etc

Also class here: Student romance. Use for: genres of romance fiction often set in an academic environment such as a university or a college campus or an academy, usually featuring university aged characters discovering life as newly adult people, getting their first taste of adult love, romance and often sexual experience. Use with: 5LKE if the main characters and the storyline concern the newly adult or those young adults who have left home for the first time

Use for: romance stories set in the past (typically before the writer’s lifetime), where the time period is a significant or essential part of the story, and that portray the spirit, manners, and social conditions of that time with realistic detail (e.g. Regency romances, Victorian romances, US Civil War, Gilded Age, Belle Epoch romance, Arthurian romance, Medieval or Renaissance romance, Tudor romance, Romances set in the Ancient world or romances featuring Vikings, pirates, Scottish highlanders, knights, etc). Use with: PLACE 1* and/or TIME PERIOD 3* Qualifiers to indicate setting as appropriate,

Also class here: cowboy, cowgirl, frontier, rancher, rodeo, gaucho, vaquero romances. Use for: romance that takes place in very rural environments, often set on farms, ranches, haciendas, or in small rural communities, usually far from any city and often set in the Western parts of the USA, Mexico or Canada, the pampas of South America, the Australian outback or similar environments. Use with: PLACE 1* Qualifiers to describe setting and TIME PERIOD 3* for historical settings

Also class here: Romance stories featuring extramarital love affairs, cheating love triangles, love triangle jealousy, or other stories featuring some sort of love triangle. Use for: romance stories usually featuring a triangle of relationships and typically involving two people who are competing for the third person’s romantic attention or one person in love with two different people

Also class here: second chance romance, neighbours to lovers, roommates to lovers, opposite attracts, unlikely loves, forbidden love, unforeseen romance, Grump and sunshine romances, sworn off love, etc. Use for: Romance where the plot revolves around a significant change or an adaptation of the nature of an existing relationship between the main characters
Use for: romance stories where the main characters initially have a relationship based on friendship that gradually changes into a strong attraction
Also class here: Rivals to lovers’ romance, Frenemies. Use for: romance stories where the main characters initially have a conflicting relationship that gradually changes into a strong attraction

Also class here: fake-dating, false relationships, fake boyfriend or girlfriend, marriage of convenience romances. Use for: romance stories where the main characters initially have some sort of fake or pretend romantic relationship

Also class here: Stuck together romances, Only-one-bed romances, road trip romances, trapped together romances. Use for: romance stories where the main characters initially are thrown together into close proximity for various reason
Use for: a romance story that also involves a mystery, crime, suspense or thriller storyline but remains primarily a romance story. Use with: other F* genre fiction codes as appropriate

Also class here: Athlete Romance, Football romance, hockey romance, baseball romance, cricket romance, soccer romance, etc. Use for: Romance featuring participants in sports, sports stars, athletes, coaches, owners, agents, sports teams, sporting events, sporting activities or any romance where the sports element is an integral part of the story. Use with: S* codes to indicate which sport is the key aspect of the romance story

Also class here: military, armed services, armed forces, security, sailors, aircrew, law enforcement, soldiers, sheriffs, cops, firefighters, police, pilots, cabin crew etc. Use for: romance stories where one or more of the main protagonists is in a job that means wearing a formal uniform
Use for: romance stories featuring doctors, nurses, surgeons, veterinarians, or any professional medical setting, such as a hospital or clinic, etc

Also class here: Rockstar romance, Rags to riches romance, Millionaire or Billionaire romance, Secret Billionaire romance, Celebrity romance, Royal romance. Use for: genres of romance fiction featuring persons in position of great wealth, power, status or similar, such as the jet set, super-rich, billionaires, royalty, aristocrats, rock stars, celebrities, high society, celebrity meets a non-celebrity and they fall in love, romance story featuring an ordinary person and a very rich, powerful, famous person, or romance fiction featuring at least one of the main characters who is royal or aristocratic or other inherited positions and titles, or featuring a royal kingdom or aristocratic domain, royal meets a non-royal and they fall in love, romance story featuring an ordinary person and an aristocratic or royal personage, etc. Use with: 5PDM* or other 5* INTEREST Qualifiers as appropriate

Also class here: ‘why choose’ romances, harem or reverse harem romances, polyamory romance. Use for: Romance or love stories featuring things like, open relationships, polyamorous relationships, polyandry, polyfidelity, consensual non-monogamy or non-exclusive relationships, or stories featuring multiple lovers, partners or romantic interests. Use with: VFVG2 for romances about polyamory, and with INTEREST 5* Qualifiers as appropriate

Also class here: vampire romance, were / shifter romance, supernatural romance, monster romance, alien romance, fantasy romance, paranormal romance. Use for: a romance story which blends elements from the fantasy genre or features mythical creatures or supernatural elements but remain primarily and recognisably a romance story, where the main plot revolves around a romance, with a fantasy or paranormal setting or with fantasy elements included. Use with: FM* or VXQ* codes as appropriate, for example for romance stories featuring a romance with vampires, werewolves or shapeshifters use with VXQM2, featuring demons with VXQM5, for angels, VXPS, ghosts, VXQG, witches VXWT, aliens VXQB, etc, See also: FMR

Also class here: romance and love stories based on travelling to a past or future time via time loops, time machines, time slips, time portals, accidental time travel, alternate timestreams, time war, temporal paradoxes, experiencing time in reverse, communication from the future, being stuck in a time-loop, accidental time travel

Use for: genre romance stories where the themes are darker, usually featuring an anti-hero or non-heroic characters and/or distressing situations, often exploring themes such as the darker side of power dynamics in a relationship, questionable morals or ethics, they may feature trauma and violence, or they may deal with darker psychological themes of evil or horror in society. Use with: 5X if appropriate

Also class here: Rebel and outsider romance, Mafia romance, Mob romance, MC Romance, Motorcycle Club Romance, Rogues, Rebels, and Rakes romance, Bad boy romance, Bad girl romance, Alpha Male romance, Bully romance, Biker romance, MMA romance, Fighter romance, or romances featuring characters such as assassins, criminals, outlaws, bandits, or morally grey characters. Use for: romance genre stories where one of the main protagonist is often a very strong, possessive, confident, and dominant male or female character, or romances where the main character works for, or is involved with, crime or criminal organisations, or is seen as an anti-hero, a wrongdoer, an outsider, or to have a bad or dangerous character, or is morally ambiguous, but the “bad” character will usually have a redeeming side or a change during the story. Use with: FJ* for action and adventure stories, with FHR or FFL for romance stories featuring organised crime, and with INTEREST 5* Qualifiers as appropriate. Prefer: FRV for romance stories with darker themes, See also: FRV

Also class here: Spicy romance, Steamy romance. Use for: romance fiction which contains explicit sexual content, or where the plot of the love story revolves around the sex, but which remains primarily and recognisably a romance story. Use with: INTEREST Qualifier 5X as appropriate, and with 5PRD for erotic romance stories revolving around BDSM, fetish or kink sex and other qualifiers and FR* codes as appropriate. DO NOT USE: with FP code, See also: FP

Code.CodeDescription: Family life fiction / Stories about family
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: family dramas, inter-family stories, family rivalries, stories about siblings, brother-sister stories, stories about twins, parent and child stories, etc. Use for: novels of domestic or small-scale family life, often with a focus on the relationships within a family – of any type – but not of the FT* Generational sagas genre. Use with: other F* codes as appropriate, See also: FT

Also class here: Multigenerational family sagas. Use for: genre novels which chronicle the lives and fortunes of a family or a number of related or interconnected families over a period of time and often over generations. These are often part of a sequence of novels. Use with: FR* codes for Romantic sagas or with FV when the historical setting is particularly important, for example for epic historical family sagas and PLACE 1* and/or TIME PERIOD 3* Qualifiers to indicate setting as appropriate. DO NOT USE: for traditional Icelandic or Old Norse sagas, See also: FS

Also class here: Comedic stories, comedy fiction, funny and comic novels. Use for: fiction where humour is the primary aim and feature except prefer genre-specific ‘humorous’ headings where available. Use with: other F* codes as appropriate, for humorous genre fiction
Use for: humorous fiction which is satirical and/or which parodies existing fiction, genres or writers, See also: WHP FYH

Use for: stories set in the past (typically before the writer’s lifetime), where the time period is a significant or essential part of the story and that portray the spirit, manners, and social conditions of that time with realistic detail. Use with: other F* codes as appropriate and PLACE 1* and/or TIME PERIOD 3* Qualifiers to indicate setting as appropriate. Prefer: genre-specific ‘historical’ headings where available, See also: FFH FJH FMH FRH

Also class here: faith-inspired or inspirational fiction. Use for: fiction designed to promote a particular religious, spiritual or visionary message. Use with: 5PG* values from INTEREST 5* Qualifiers as appropriate, or where unavailable, a QR* or VX* code and with other F* codes, for example FR* for Religious romance novels, with VX* codes for visionary or spiritual fiction, with 5PGM for Christian Fiction, etc

Code.CodeDescription: Fiction / Literature / Comics / Graphic novels: narrative themes
Code.CodeNotes: Use all FX* codes for: identifying the primary theme of a narrative work, when that theme is not conveyed by the choice of a genre fiction or manga, comic book or graphic novel category. Use all FX* codes with: FB* codes or other F* codes indicating genre or type, or with Literature DB*, DC*, DD* or Comics (Graphic novel / Comic book / Manga etc): genre XQ* codes, to indicate the principal underlying narrative theme of a work of fiction, literature, poetry, drama theatre, comic books etc. FX* codes can also be used in conjunction with non-fiction categories to give greater definition to the narrative theme where appropriate, FX itself can be used with a non-fiction code if there is not a suitable other FX* code. DO NOT USE: FX* codes as the primary or main subject code or simply to indicate a mood or emotion evoked by a story
Also class here: bildungsroman, growing up, rites of passage, passage from childhood or youth to adulthood as narrative themes, stories about a young person going from being a child to being an adult

Code.CodeDescription: Narrative theme: books and the world of books
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: stories, novels and works of fiction where the main theme is about the world of books, including, booksellers, bookshops, libraries, literature, writers, the art of writing, books about reading, books about books, book clubs, publishers or any story that has a main theme taken from the world of books

Use for: fiction where a strong relationship or love is the central theme but which is not a genre romance novel. This can include friendships, found family, family relationships, sibling relationships, parent-child relationships, any form of affective relationship, relationships between couples, relationships that are negative or hostile, or complex emotional relationships, forbidden love, a love triangle, unrequited love, love of family, relationships amongst a group of friends or a peer group, examination of relationships with others, acquaintances, strangers etc, as long as it is one of the principal themes of the story. Use with: INTEREST 5* Qualifiers for detail of specific kinds of relationships as appropriate. DO NOT USE: with FR* codes

Code.CodeDescription: Narrative theme: environmental issues / the natural world
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: fiction that addresses a specific environmental issue or nature-orientated topics as a central theme. Use with: other subject codes to give more specific definition to the topic if appropriate, for example, FD*, FL* , FF* or FH* codes for Climate fiction (Cli-fi), Eco-fiction or eco-thrillers or FB* for nature writing in fiction, or with XQ* codes for comic books, graphic novels or manga that have major themes around the natural world or the environment

Use for: fiction or stories that feature animals or any living creature as a major or significant part of the plot or theme, or where human interactions or relationships with animals, including pets, is a main part of the plot, or one or more of the main characters or protagonists are animals. Use with: WN* codes if the story is about a specific type of animal, for example, WNGC for stories about cats, or WNGD for stories about dogs

Use for: works of fiction that take place during periods of war or armed conflict or civil strife, and where the experience or consequences of war, or battle or armed conflict is the major theme or topic of the story and is explored through the plot or the development of the main characters. Prefer: FJM* codes for action and adventure war fiction, See also: FJM*

Use for: fiction where health, coping or living with illness – physical or mental – or the consequences of sickness is a central theme, or themes based on medical topics or suffering linked to physical or mental health, chronic illness or conditions, chronic pain, or themes around the healing, recovery or recuperation from illness

Use for: fiction where death, dying, the end-of-life, a loss or the experience of grief or mourning is a central theme and one of the key elements of the story, but not for genre fiction like crime, thriller or adventure novels that happen to have a death in them

Code.CodeDescription: Narrative theme: interior life / psychological fiction
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: psychological realism, character-driven psychological stories, stories with an interior monologue or stream of consciousness. Use for: fiction which places particular emphasis on interior characterization, and on the motives, emotions, feelings and thoughts or mental lives of characters, stories that explore the mental state of a character. Prefer: FHX for psychological thrillers, See also: FHX

Use for: fiction where the identity, the sense of, or search for, identity of whatever kind – social, cultural, religious, gender etc, as an individual or part of a group – of the main character(s) is the main, or one of the main themes of the story, or narratives where the characters sense of belonging or search or need for belonging is the main or major theme of the plot. Use with: other subject codes and INTEREST 5* Qualifiers as appropriate

Also class here: Political novels, fiction as political or economic criticism, novels of political satire, fiction as commentary or discussion on politics, economics, society, government, diplomacy, politicians or political culture, political power, political corruption as major themes of a story. Use for: fiction or literature where political or economic concerns are the underlying narrative theme including political or economic allegories. Use with: DC* for political poetry. Prefer: FHP for political thrillers, See also: FHP

Use for: fiction that has major themes relating to diasporas, dispersion, asylum, deracination, forced relocation, cultural transitions, forced journeys, living in exile, being exiled, emigration, expatriation, immigration, refugees, forced resettlement, etc, See also: FXV

Use for: fiction set in a real location where the setting or landscape very deeply pervades the work to the extent that it could not be set anywhere else; e.g. the French tradition of ‘roman du terroir’. Use with: PLACE 1* Qualifiers, and other subject codes for example, with JBSD for novels where city life is a main theme, or JBSG for reservation life or rez lit, or JBSE for small town life novels, JBSC for works of fiction where the setting in a small town, village, a rural area, or in the countryside and the associated lifestyle or living conditions are critical to the sense and meaning of the story

Code.CodeDescription: Narrative theme: social issues / social problems
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: Social protest novels, fiction as social commentary, stories about social unrest.
