Use for: fiction that addresses a specific social problem or issue as a central theme, such as, poverty or precarity, economic inequalities, homelessness, housing issues, conditions in factories and mines, the plight of child labour, violence against women, rising criminality, and epidemics because of over-crowding and poor sanitation in cities or works of fiction in which a prevailing social problem, such as gender, race, or class prejudice, is dramatized through its effect on the characters of a novel. Use with: other non-fiction codes, especially JBF* codes, to give more detail of the main social issue but an F* code MUST be designated as the Main Subject

Code.CodeDescription: Narrative theme: diversity, equity, equality, inclusion
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: works of fiction where the main narrative theme or subject matter clearly illustrates topics relating to aspects of accessibility, social justice, equity or equality, diversity and inclusivity within the context of the story, or the story explores themes of DEI, or attempts to achieve DEI. Use with: other subject codes and INTEREST 5* Qualifiers to give greater detail as appropriate

Also class here: road trip stories, stories about voyages of exploration and discovery, stories about quests, epic journeys or about wanderers. Use for: fiction where a journey, expedition, voyage or some sort of travel or trip is the main or a major narrative theme of the story, See also: FXQ

Code.CodeDescription: Fiction / Literature / Comics / Graphic novels: special features
Code.CodeNotes: Use all FY* codes with: other F* code indicating genre or subject, or with literature DB*, DC*, DD* or Comics (Graphic novel / Comic book / Manga etc), genre XQ* codes, to indicate the principal underlying distinct aspects, attributes, characteristic or features of a work of fiction. FY* codes should not usually be the primary or main subject code. DO NOT USE: FY itself - always use FY* codes
Also class here: Anthologies or collections of short works of fiction either by the same author or by multiple authors. Use with: DNT for anthologies of short stories by theme or by multiple authors
Use for: works of fiction that are neither seen as short stories nor as novels by their creators
Use for: fiction, literature, comic books or any fictional narratives that are written in a series of documents, letters, diaries, journals, emails, blogs, social media posts, etc

Also class here: Continuation novels. Use for: works of fiction where a new author continues an established series after the original authors death. These can be official with the permission of the literary estate or unofficial for works now out of copyright. These stories may be sequels to the original series or be stories that are prequels or precede the original storyline, but all the stories are written after the original authors death
Use for: fiction written deliberately in the style of another (typically earlier) author (as homage rather than parody), See also: FUP

Also class here: Past-Present narratives. Use for: fiction, literature, comic books or any fictional narratives that have storylines featuring two or more timelines (but where there is no time travelling or time slips), where a single cohesive narrative, is told using multiple time periods and perspectives

Use for: fiction, literature, comic books or any fictional narratives that are usually create an atmosphere of tension and suspense for the reader using psychological techniques and often feature themes things like a sense of fear and haunting, gloom or death, a dark past, a claustrophobic atmosphere, an oppressive, bleak, decayed or derelict setting, the threat of supernatural events, and the intrusion of the past upon the present and that often inspire fear through a romanticized view of the past, and often combining elements of both horror and romance etc. Use with: FR* for Gothic romance, FK* for Gothic horror, other F* codes for other types of Gothic fiction, with PLACE1* Qualifiers for gothic fiction associated with a particular area, such as 1KBB-US-S* codes - for Southern Gothic (USA) or 1KL* codes for gothic fiction set in Latin America

Also class here: mash-up or mashed-up novels. Use for: fiction which combines a pre-existing text, often a classic novel, with another contrasting genre, such as horror, into a single narrative, or that takes fictional characters, settings, or universes from different fictions and places them into a single story. Use with: other F* or non-fiction codes to indicate component elements, See also: FUP

Code.CodeDescription: Fiction based on or inspired by true events
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: fiction based on or inspired by a true event or happening but where this is told in narrative fictionalised form and is not just an account of the event itself. Use with: other F* codes to describe the genre or with Literature DB*, DC*, DD*, comic books XQ* codes. Prefer: DNX for narrative accounts of true stories, or FC for fiction based on peoples lives, See also: DNX FC

Code.CodeDescription: Fiction: special features: yaoi / BL / danmei novels
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: boys’ love novels. Use for: East Asian style stories, often related to comics or anime, featuring male same-sex relationships, created principally, but not exclusively, for a female readership. Use with: other F* codes to indicate genre, for example FR* codes for Romance stories, 5LKE * codes if they are about that generation, See also: XAMT

Use for: the kind of romance, science fiction or other types of genre fiction or comic books, usually published on a monthly basis, short, in clearly delineated lines and with a certain number published every month. Use with: other F* code indicating genre or type, for example, with FR*codes for Category or Series Romance. DO NOT USE: FYR as the main or primary subject or the only code

Also class here: Raito noberu, Japanese novellas, illustrated novellas. Use for: short fiction aimed at adults, usually driven primarily by dialogue and character and generally accompanied by illustrations in manga/anime or similar styles. Use with: other F* codes to indicate the genre. FYS may be used as a main subject as appropriate

Use for: fiction and literature translated from another language. Use with: F* or with Literature DB*, DC*, DD*, or comic book XQ* codes to ensure classification is meaningful beyond the translation of the work itself and with 5T* - Literature of Place Qualifiers as appropriate. DO NOT USE: PLACE 1* or LANGUAGE 2* Qualifiers to specify the original language (this is described in other metadata). You may still use a PLACE 1* Qualifier if it is relevant to the plot or setting of the book. DO NOT USE: FYT as the main or primary subject or the only code

Code.CodeDescription: Fiction: inspired by or adapted from other media
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: stories that were published as spin-offs or companions to pre-existing non-book media or merchandise, novelizations and novels inspired by a popular film franchise, an online game or a TV series. Use with: other F* codes indicating genre or type, or with Literature DB*, DC*, DD* codes if this work is presented as a poem or a play, or XQ* for comic book. DO NOT USE: for titles that were subsequently made into films, film tie-in versions (this is described in other metadata)

Code.CodeDescription: Fiction: special features: game-related / LitRPG stories
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: GameLit, RoLit, Game lit, literary role-playing game. Use for: fiction that is structured like a videogame or role playing game, or features the same kind of challenges as would be found in any type of game, or is about or set in a videogame, an online game, a role playing game, etc. Use with: other F* codes especially FL* or FM* as appropriate, or with Literature DB*, DC*, DD* codes if this work is presented as a poem or play or XQ* for comic book

Use for: companion works to popular fiction or comic book series or titles, typically uncritical, such as an atlas or map of a mythical world or fictional universe, a compendium of characters or objects, to the flora, fauna or geography of the place, a guide to the series, art inspired by or taken from the series, a cookery book or crafts inspired by the series, etc. Use with: other F* codes indicating genre or type, or with Literature DB*, DC*, DD* or comic book XQ* codes if this work is presented as a poem or a comic book etc. Prefer: DS* codes for critiques or critical works, See also: DSR XR* DS*

Use all G* codes for: specialist and general adult titles. DO NOT USE: code ‘G’ itself, but select specific categories from section G*. Use all G* codes with: other subject categories and qualifiers where appropriate
Use for: non-subject-specific works only
Use with: other subject code indicating the area or scope of the work, See also: CB* DSR*
Also class here: Who’s Who. Use with: other subject code indicating the area or scope of the work
Use for: dictionaries and glossaries covering a particular subject e.g. Legal dictionaries. Use with: other subject codes as appropriate

Use for: reference works that present a subject primarily through maps, charts, infographics, data visualisation, visual timelines or other mainly visual presentation of information. Use with: other subject codes and qualifiers indicating the area or scope of the work. DO NOT USE: just to indicate a work is illustrated, use only when the work would not be understandable without the visuals, See also: RGX
Also class here: collections of common phrases or aphorisms, helpful quotations for specific purposes
See also: AVD
Use for: works listing individuals or organisations (generally arranged alphabetically, thematically, phonetically, etc) with details such as names, addresses, and telephone numbers

Use for: works containing a mixture or assortment of pieces compiled from varied sources and that can include many subjects and be in a variety of different forms, such as quotes, facts, illustrations etc. Use with: other subject codes when the miscellany covers one broad subject, (e.g. for a bestiary use with WN* codes), See also: WDKX

Code.CodeDescription: IT, Internet and electronic resources in libraries

Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: indexing, cataloguing and classification
Also class here: academic, specialist, public and school libraries; reference, circulation and community services

Also class here: museum studies, curatorship, heritage interpretation, and historical conservation, collection management, museum administration, conservation of cultural heritage. Use for: works about the preservation and promotion of culturally and socially significant sites, buildings, monuments, the tangible, intangible and natural cultural heritage of a society, the historic environment, preserved cultural heritage, etc, See also: ABC AGC NK* RNK TNKX WTHM

Also class here: orality as a means of transmitting knowledge from generation to generation, use of oral storytelling for teaching and transmission of knowledge, Oral interpretation. Use for: works that look at the use of oral communication of stories, sacred narratives, texts, literature, kinship, music, laws, knowledge, learning, traditions, healing, natural world, agriculture or any other cultural element, or about the nature of oral story telling, orality and its important in different cultures, etc. Use with: other subject codes to indicate particular subject areas, See also: DH JBGB
Also class here: control and stability of systems, entropy

Also class here: data visualization and infographics, large data sets, big data, data governance, data analytics. Use for: interdisciplinary works about data, data management and its uses in other disciplines, works about techniques, methods, processes, algorithms, used to extract or extrapolate knowledge, information or insights from data, structured or unstructured). Use with: other subject codes as appropriate, See also: UN* UX* UYZF
Also class here: cryptography, See also: URY
See also: KJMD
Also class here: risk management, risk analysis. Use with: other codes for works about risks in different sectors

Also class here: works on research methodology, research design, research proposals, research strategies, basic or fundamental research methods, Experimental research methods, research writings, writing for publication and presentation of research papers, comparative research methodology. Use with: other subject codes for research methods within a particular discipline. Prefer: subject codes alone for work about a subject even if it was based on or the result of research, See also: JHBC KJT
Also class here: Empirical research questions. Use with: other subject codes for empirical research methods or strategy within a particular discipline
Use with: other subject codes for quantitative research methods or strategy within a particular discipline
Use with: other subject codes for qualitative research methods or strategy within a particular discipline

Also class here: Applied research strategy, action research, evaluation research, research and development, practical applications of research, applying research to solve practical problems. Use with: other subject codes for applied research within a particular discipline

Also class here: Interdisciplinarity. Use all GT* codes with: other subject categories and qualifiers for works about different types of ‘Studies’, usually academic that include multiple subjects or disciplines, or works that are about cross-disciplinary research

Code.CodeDescription: History of scholarship (principally of social sciences and humanities)
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: historical studies concentrating on fields of study not covered by the English term ‘science’ (cf. history of science), but included for example in the German term ‘Wissenschaft’ (i.e. all kinds of academic studies), See also: PDA PDX

Also class here: Communication science. Use for: Communication Studies textbooks and for works covering a range of aspects of communication – linguistic, social, industrial, technological etc, works that look at ways of communication, or the means used to communicate, the means of transmission of information, Augmentative and Alternative Communication techniques, See also: JBCT*
See also: CFA

Code.CodeDescription: Reception or Interpretation studies / Audience Theory
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: Hermeneutics, Interpretation of text, theories and methodologies of interpretation, or of audience reception. Use for: Interdisciplinary topics that examine how something has been perceived at different times, how things have been interpretated or how an audience has reacted to it. Use with: JBC* for audience theory in Media Studies, DBSS for Classical Reception Studies, QD* for Hermeneutics or Interpretation as a philosophical discipline or QR* for hermeneutics or interpretation in religion, especially with QRVC for the interpretation of sacred texts, NK* codes for interpretation in archaeology, ATFA for reception studies in film, DS* for reception studies and theories in literary criticism, etc
Use for: interdisciplinary works, See also: QDTM JM* MKJ PSAN UYQ* UXJ

Also class here: area studies, global studies. Use for: interdisciplinary works covering a range of topics within a defined geographical, cultural or linguistic area. Use with: PLACE 1*, LANGUAGE 2* Qualifiers as appropriate, See also: RGL
See also: KCM

Also class here: epistemological or epistemic decolonization, decolonialism, works that explore the widening of an approach to knowledge or to what is studied and how it is studied. Use with: other subject codes for works that examine this in the context of a specific topic

Also class here: vexillology, symbology. Use for: general works about one or any of these topics. Use with: other subject categories as appropriate, for example, use with QR* codes for religious symbols, use with KJS* codes for logos or symbols used in marketing, VXW* codes for symbols associated with different mystical or magical traditions, See also: NHTG
Also class here: transitional justice, Reconciliation Studies, Peacebuilding, Peacekeeping, Peace and Reconciliation Studies, Transformative Justice as part of reconciliation, See also: JWLP
See also: JPSN

Use for: usually interdisciplinary material aimed specifically at General Studies courses at undergraduate level or general knowledge and cultural information for adult education. Use with: with 4CN*, 4CP* or 4TN* for tests, See also: WDKX YPWL

Use all J* codes for: specialist and some general adult titles, but see also V* codes for practical approaches to many topics. Use all J* codes with: other subject categories and qualifiers where appropriate. In J* use the most appropriate code(s) available, as many social sciences are broad topics that can have many alternative terms or names

Use all JB* codes for: both general and academic works on social topics, general works about culture and society. Use with: JH* codes for sociology textbooks and other specialist works as appropriate, See also: VFV*
Also class here: general works on media and culture studies, works about the relationship between media and society, culture and cultural topics and their relationship to media

Also class here: intercultural studies, studies of cultural identity, general studies of cultural heritage, contemporary culture in society, cultural sociology. Use with: PLACE 1*, LANGUAGE 2* or 5P* INTEREST Qualifiers to indicate the cultural studies of a particular region(s) or country / countries, language grouping or groups of people
Also class here: Contemporary culture, pop culture, mass culture, culture of fame or celebrity, fan culture, fan studies, fandoms

Use for: the interdisciplinary field telling of relationships between people and their things, the role of artefacts and objects in society, the making, history, preservation, and interpretation of objects

Also class here: changing ideas of beauty or body image in culture and how individuals dress the body, works on aspects of attire, clothing, costumes, dress or fashions in different cultures or societies, or works that look at how dress is used within societies to communicate social status and social role, cross dressing in different cultures, etc. Use with: NHTB for an historical approach or AKT* codes as appropriate

Also class here: Food writing, cultural aspects of food and gastronomy, cultural aspects of cultivating, foraging, gathering, harvesting or hunting for food. Use for: works that examine the traditions, habits, customs, rituals, ceremonies, taboos linked to food and drink in different cultures, food or drink as intangible cultural heritage. Use with: NHTB for an historical approach and with WB* codes as appropriate, See also: WB

Also class here: studies of traditional rituals and ceremonies; cultural taboos or superstitions, social behaviour, values and norms as defined by society, institutions, traditions and cultural beliefs, studies of Intangible cultural heritage, traditional cultural expressions, traditional knowledge, cultural practices, etc, See also: JBGB

Also class here: Comparative studies, cross-cultural encounters, cross-cultural exchanges, cross-cultural clashes, intercultural relations, intercultural communication, interculturalism, cross-cultural conflicts, clashes of values or beliefs. Use for: works that examine social and cultural topics and issues around the meeting of or interactions between different cultures, including conflicts, negative or positive exchanges, on a personal or a societal level. Use with: NH* codes for historical topics

Use for: works about current debates, policies, ideas, controversies around the role of culture or cultural heritage in society, debates about clashes of cultural values or beliefs, debates about cultural imperialism, cultural diversity, the nature of culture, social and political policies linked to culture, debates about funding and political policies in culture
Use for: works that look at the expression, preservation, and change of human ideas over time. Use with: other J* or NH* or QD* codes as appropriate
Also class here: Media culture, Infotainment, Mass media. Use for: works that deal with the content, history, and effects of various type of mass communication media, See also: GTC

Code.CodeDescription: Media studies: internet, digital media and society
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: all aspects of online, digital and social media and their role or impact in society, including things such as blogging, tweeting, influencers, spread of real and false information, changing habits and behaviour linked to digital media, See also: ATN
Use for: works on both traditional and new forms of consuming small screen entertainment, including streaming and on demand services, impacts and influences on culture, links to popular culture, etc
Also class here: the Press, newspapers, news media, journalists and reporters, online and print journalism, communicating news and events, See also: KNTP

Also class here: propaganda, ‘fake news’, post-truth politics, ‘alternative facts’, doctored and fake photos, images, videos, deepfakes, use of artificial intelligence to falsify data or images. Use for: works about the purposeful use of false or misleading information, manipulation of thoughts and actions by use of information, the spread of misleading or non-fact based information, the selective use of facts, information or news stories, planting of stories in mass media. Use with: JBCT1 for works about the role of digital platforms or social media, with JBGX for misinformation or disinformation linked to conspiracy theories, See also: KJST JBGX
Use with: other categories to indicate works that treat a subject as part of a social, cultural or ethical debate and where there is no specific JBF* code, See also: PDR QDTQ RNT

Also class here: social exclusion, social inequalities, social marginalisation, diversity studies, hate speech, hate or bias crimes, intersectionality. Use for: works about various forms of discrimination, about equality or inequality, about prejudice based on a person’s identity, about systemic or institutional bias, and also about measures to address these issues, such as diversity, equity and inclusion (DEI) policies or topics, equal treatment, positive discrimination, work on unconscious bias. Use with: other JB* categories, or other subject categories and Qualifiers to denote specific forms of discrimination, e.g. with JBSF* codes for sexism or discrimination based on sex or gender, QRAM9 plus 5PG* codes for discrimination based on religion or beliefs, JBSJ plus 5PS* codes for sexual prejudice or discrimination based on sexual orientation, JBFM and 5PM* Qualifiers for ableism or discrimination based on ability or disability, JBSA and 5PD* for discrimination based on class or socioeconomic status, with JBSP* and 5L* for discrimination based on age

Also class here: institutional racism, xenophobia, antisemitism. Use for: works about discrimination and prejudice based on skin colour, race or ethnic origin, or prejudices based on the perception that someone is foreign or from outside the community, and issues of inequality and discrimination, works that explore institutional or systemic racism, racial segregation, as well as measures to address racism, or to advance conversations about race, for works that look at other identities or perceptions of an identity, such as beliefs or religion, where the prejudice becomes or is treated as a form of racism. Use with: other J* codes for works about racism in particular domains and with 5P* INTEREST Qualifiers to indicate works about racism aimed at particular groups, for example, with 5PBD for works about racism aimed at those of African descent, with 5PGJ for works about racism aimed at Jewish people or on racial antisemitism, with 5PBA for works about racism against Indigenous groups, with 5PBR for racism against Romani or Travellers, etc

Code.CodeDescription: Social or cultural Integration and assimilation
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: full assimilation, assimilationism, acculturation, cultural integration. Use with: NH* codes for works that look at historical cultural or social integration

Also class here: forced religious conversion, forced cultural assimilation, forced cultural changes, or the use of educational, religious, official organisations or other institutions to eliminate cultures, languages, beliefs, individual or collective identities, or to force assimilation by a dominant, invader or colonial culture on a pre-existing cultural identity. Use with: NH* codes for history titles, such as NHTQ when linked to colonialism, NHTZ when linked to historical genocides, NHTT when linked to invasion, QRAM9 when linked to religious intolerance of other beliefs, JPFN when linked to Nationalism, etc

Also class here: the economically disadvantaged, extreme poverty, poverty threshold, works about food poverty or food insecurity, food banks, unemployment or employment when linked to poverty, the precariat, economic insecurity, underemployment, chaotic lifestyles, malnutrition linked to poverty, in-work poverty, the working poor, economic or income inequalities, economic disparity, wealth inequality
Also class here: the unhoused, issues around providing houses, cost of homes, lack of accommodation, etc

Code.CodeDescription: Social impact of disasters / accidents (natural or man-made)
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: works about the consequences, on people and society, of natural, or human-made, emergencies, disasters and accidents; including things like: plagues, epidemics, pandemics, famines, volcanic eruptions, earthquakes, extreme weather, severe storms, floods, droughts, fires, crashes, shipwrecks, maritime and air disasters or accidents, rail or road accidents, explosions, oil spills, getting trapped or lost, etc. Use with: VSY for titles that explain how to prepare for disasters, for example, what to do during an earthquake, or major fire or tsunami, etc, See also: RNR
Also class here: asylum seekers, sanctuary. Use with: other codes for specific topics, such as JBFA for discrimination, JBFD for housing topics, NHTB for social history, FX for novels, etc

Also class here: the Underground Railroad, the Comet Line, Fluchthilfe, etc. Use for: titles about helping refugees escape repression, slavery, conflicts etc. Use with: NH* codes and PLACE 1* and TIME PERIOD 3* Qualifiers as appropriate

Use for: works about diasporas, the expatriates, settlers or migrants themselves, or cultural or social topics linked to migration. Use with: other codes for specific topics, such as JBFA for discrimination, JBFD for housing topics, NHTB for social history, N* codes for the history of human migrations, movements and settlement, the Historical expansion, movement and migrations of groups of peoples across land and sea, historical movements of populations, movements of colonists, settlers, nomads and nomadic groups, migration stories, FX for novels, etc, See also: RGCG

Code.CodeDescription: Forced displacements, removals or population transfers
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: forced migration, forced relocation, forced population resettlement, involuntary migration, mass expulsions of peoples. Use with: N* codes for works about historical events and with relevant PLACE 1K* or 1QB* and TIME PERIOD 3* Qualifiers,, See also: NHTZ

Also class here: Contemporary slavery, forced labour, forced marriage, sexual slavery, modern-day slavery, forced prostitution, child labour, debt bondage, bonded labour, compelled labour, descent-based slavery, child slavery, child marriage, domestic servitude, or works about enslaved people or people who have been trafficked or are victims of modern slavery, human trafficking or sex trafficking, See also: NHTS

Also class here: ill-treatment, maltreatment or wilful neglect in society, violence based on cultural traditions, violence against particular groups or individuals, violent civil disorders, group or mob violence in society, vigilante justice, institutional violence, violent criminal behaviour in society etc. Use for: works about perceptions of violence and insecurity in society, as well as works on actual violence, abuse and neglect. Use with: JBSF* codes for gender-based violence, See also: JKV
Also class here: child neglect
Also class here: sexual violence, rape, sexual assault. Use with: JBSF1 for works about sexual violence against women and girls, See also: JKVN

Also class here: domestic violence, family violence, intimate partner violence, coercive control, gaslighting, master suppression techniques and countermeasures. Use with: JBSF1 for works about domestic violence against women and girls

Also class here: mobbing, social media trolling, cyberbullying, intimidation, coercion, stalking and threatening behaviour. Use with: JBCT* codes when linked to different kinds of media, KNXC or KJMV2 for workplace harassment

Code.CodeDescription: Control, privacy and safety in society
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: issues and debates around privacy, use of data, the role of government and big corporations, security, anti-terrorism, rights of the individual versus the rights of society, surveillance, public safety, social control and coercion, See also: JPV

Also class here: Ableism, disablism, social aspects of neurodiversity, accessibility, inclusive practices. Use for: works that look at societal barriers to a person with impairments, the way societies treat disabled persons, the impact of policies, works about any form of discrimination, negative attitudes, assumptions or prejudice towards groups or individuals based on ability or disability, and works that look at ways to address these discriminations, address stereotypes, assumptions, social justice, etc. Use with: 5PM* Qualifiers as appropriate and other codes for specific topics, such as JBFA for discrimination, JBFD for housing topics, JKS* for welfare, NHTB for social history, FX for novels etc

Code.CodeDescription: Health, illness or addiction: social aspects
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: studies of the social or cultural impact of health policies or different illnesses or addictions; social or cultural behaviour or reactions to different types of addictions, illnesses, diseases or health scares, works that look at the social aspects of access or lack of access to health services, healthcare, health education, topics linked to the social aspects of planning access to health care, problems linked to lack of access or restrictions to healthcare services, etc. Use with: MBP to indicate social aspects of health systems

Also class here: drug or alcohol addiction, opioid addiction, substance abuse, recreational drug use, use of drugs for ritual or spiritual reasons. Use for: works about impact of drugs and alcohol addiction or abuse on society, groups or individuals, intervention strategies, public drug policies, debates on legalisation or prohibition of certain drugs or alcohol, societal approaches and attitudes to substances such as cannabis, recreational drug use, drinking culture, binge drinking, rehabilitation, violence and crime linked to drugs and alcohol, impact on the young, on marginalised groups and communities etc

Also class here: Social reproduction. Use for: works about the movement of individuals or groups from one socio-economic group to another, or the ability to do this, or government policies to facilitate social mobility, or works about the maintenance and continuation of existing social relations, the opposite of social mobility. Use with: JBSA and 5PD* qualifiers as appropriate

Code.CodeDescription: Animals and society / Animal rights - issues and debates
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: works that look at debates around topics like animal rights, vivisection and experimentation on animals, hunting and other blood sports, animal welfare, the use of animals for food, as resources, or as commodities, keeping animals as pets, human impact on the animal world, debates on speciesism, and treatment of animals based on religious doctrines
Use with: other categories to indicate works that treat a subject as an ethical debate, or ethical or moral dilemmas and where there is no specific JBFV* code, See also: PSAD QDTQ

Code.CodeDescription: Ethical issues, topics and debates: reproductive health, abortion and birth control
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: debates on the access to birth control, debates about abortion and abortion services, family planning, reproductive rights, access to information about reproductive health, provision for women of sexual and reproductive healthcare and information, access to family planning
Also class here: the death penalty

Code.CodeDescription: Ethical issues: censorship / freedom of expression
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: debates around freedom of speech, censorship vs security, censorship in schools, universities and libraries, book banning and banned books, debates on limitations or restrictions to freedom of speech, freedom to protest, or works that look at government, institutions or corporations restricting freedom expressions through laws, manipulation or control of information, scapegoating marginalised groups or minorities to restrict freedoms, etc

Code.CodeDescription: Ethical issues: euthanasia and right to die
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: assisted suicide, assisted death. Use with: LNT for legal aspects

Code.CodeDescription: Ethical issues: scientific, technological and medical developments
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: Ethical challenges, debates, issues or dilemmas linked to, or the Impact on societies and culture of, things like artificial intelligence, social technology, surveillance society, mass data collection, medical advances, etc

Code.CodeDescription: Ethical issues and debates: Competing or conflicting rights
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: Value pluralism, ethical pluralism, moral pluralism. Use for: works that examine debates about when the rights of an individual or group conflict with the rights of another individual or group, or to situations where citizens’ constitutional and legal rights clash, such as debates of religious freedom versus secular freedoms, free speech versus protection from hate speech or protection of privacy, collective identity rights versus individual identity freedoms, minority versus majority rights, paradox of tolerance, balance of individual rights vs collective rights, the right to protest vs the rights or needs of state or individual security, etc

Also class here: Sex and sexuality studies, sexual cultures. Use for: general interest works on sex and society, works on social and cultural aspects of sexual and reproductive health, pornography and the sex industry, sex work and prostitution, or works that look at questions about human sexuality in particular societies, general works about how humans experience and express themselves sexually, cultural or societal attitudes towards or norms and controls around human sexuality, repression and criminalisation of sexuality, attitudes to contraception, attitudes to education and information about sex in society, etc, See also: JMU VFVC

Also class here: political correctness, societal attitudes, changing attitudes, individual or collective attitudes. Use for: general works about social, political and moral attitudes in societies. Use with: other categories for attitudes towards particular subjects or groups

Also class here: popular piety, historical superstitions, popular religion. Use with: NHTB for works looking at historical aspects of popular beliefs, or with VXQ* codes for works about particular popular beliefs about the paranormal, or unexplained phenomena, or mysteries

Use for: non-fiction studies of traditional stories or material, verbal or customary folklore; folkloristics, studies of folk religions or traditions, studies of urban and contemporary myths and legends; studies of the origins of myths, fairy tales, tall stories, paranormal tales, supernatural beings, old wives’ tales, popular superstitions etc; specialist works about the origin of the stories of things like Atlantis, the Holy Grail, the Hidden Folk, the Bermuda Triangle, the Green Man, the bogeyman etc. Prefer: QR* codes for the spiritual or religious aspects of mythology or VX* codes for more popular approaches or FN* codes for the stories themselves, See also: FN* QRS* VXQM* QR*

Also class here: hoaxes, cover ups, denialism, etc. Use for: works that examine conspiracy theories in general, or the reasons for their existence, or look at individual theories, or set out arguments for or against a particular theory, See also: JBCT5

Also class here: general works on social groups, groups with shared identities, works that look at aspects of social units with commonalities (communities), or different forms of studies of communities and their development, or works on compounded identities (intersectionality), works that look at personal or collective identities, Social stratification, general works about intersectionality or particular theories or schools of thought or research about intersectionality, or works that look how individuals’ various social and political identities result in unique combinations of discrimination and privilege. Use all JBS* codes with: other codes for specific topics, such as JBFA for discrimination, JP* codes for works on identity politics, NHTB for social history, FX* for novels and INTEREST 5* Qualifiers as appropriate

Also class here: class conflict, social stratification, socio-economic groups. Use for: works that examine class, a particular class, characteristics and distinctions of that class, interaction between different strata of society, perceptions and prejudices about particular classes. Use with: 5PD* Qualifiers to indicate works about particular socio-economic groups, with JBFQ for works about movement from one social class to another

Code.CodeDescription: Indigenous reservation / reserve communities or equivalents
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: Reservation life, Rez Lit. Use for: works that look at Indigenous groups living on reservations, reserves or equivalents, on land set aside for First Nations under Treaties, Land governed by Native American Tribal Nations, Indigenous territory or Indigenous land, Native Community Lands. Use with: F* codes for fiction where the main theme is about life on a reservation or similar communities

Also class here: small settlements in rural areas, people living in the countryside, semi-rural areas, isolated communities, farming communities, country life, rural studies, people living and working in rural areas. Use with: F* codes for rural fiction

Also class here: urban studies, life in the city, inner cities, city and town dwellers. Use for: any works on aspects of life or issues in urban or semi-urban settings and the associated communities. Use with: other subject codes for effects on urban communities or studies of things like urban decay, gentrification, commuters, urban regeneration and urban communities

Also class here: suburban lifestyles, suburbia, commuter belt communities, dormitory towns, exurbs, outskirts of metropolitan areas, people who live or work in suburban areas, studies of suburban mentalities or attitudes. Use with: F* codes for suburban fiction, or fiction where the main theme is about suburban life

Code.CodeDescription: Small town communities / small town life
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: small town life, people who live and work in small towns, studies of small town mentalities or attitudes. Use with: F* codes for small town fiction, or fiction where the main theme is about small town life

Use for: works that examine social roles based on the sex of the person (gender role) or personal identification of one’s own gender based on an internal awareness (gender identity), as well as works that look at sex (based on the anatomy of an individual’s reproductive system, and secondary sex characteristics), including intersex people. Use all JBSF* codes with: other subject codes that explore gender topics in particular areas, e.g. with MB* for works that examine gender or sex differences in medicine, or JB* for works about gender in culture, JBFA for works on gender equality or gender-based discrimination, or F* codes for fiction where the main theme is gender, etc

Also class here: Women’s studies. Use with: other subject codes when a work is primarily about women or girls, such as JBFA for discrimination based on gender or sexism or misogyny, NHTB for women’s history, JBFK* or JKVN for works that look at violence or violent crimes against women, JM* for psychology titles, VF* codes for advice on different health and wellbeing topics for women, or with DS* codes for literary studies or theory, or other subject codes as appropriate

Also class here: Women’s liberation movement, First-wave, Second-wave, Third-wave and Fourth-wave feminism, Radical feminism, Intersectional feminism, Neo-feminism, Post-feminism, Analytical feminism, Individualist feminism, Liberal or mainstream feminism, Materialist feminism, Social feminism, Post-structural feminism, Feminist separatism, Neo feminism, Post feminism, Afro-feminism, Black feminism, Indigenous feminism, Use for: general works on feminism or about particular feminist movements, theories or schools of thought. Use with: other codes for different types of feminism, such as RNA for ecofeminism, JPFB for Anarcha-feminism, QRM for Christian feminism, QRP for Islamic feminism, JPFC for Marxist Feminism, QD* for feminist topics in philosophy, JBSF3 for Transfeminism, QRVG for Feminist theology
Also class here: Men’s studies, topics around masculinity. Use with: other subject codes when a work is primarily about men or boys

Code.CodeDescription: Gender studies: ‘trans’, transgender people and gender variance
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: transsexual, transgender, gender non-conforming, non-binary, genderqueer, gender minority, two spirit, third gender etc. Use for: works that look at those whose gender is different (wholly or partially) from that assigned to them at birth, or gender variance in cultures which have established more than two genders. Use with: JBFA for issues around discrimination and transphobia / transmisia, JBFK* or JKVN for works that look at anti-trans violence or hate crimes, VF* codes for advice on different health and well being topics, etc plus 5PT Qualifier, as appropriate

Also class here: queer studies, sexual diversity studies, gay and lesbian studies, gender, sexual, and romantic minorities studies, queer theory. Use for: studies of sexuality, sexual orientation and associated identity-based groups or cultures. Use with: other codes for specific LGBTQIA+ topics, e.g. JBFA for homophobia / homomisia or issues around discrimination or NHTB for LGBTQ+ history, or JBFK* or JKVN for works that look at Anti-LGBTQ+ violence or hate crimes, VF* codes for advice on different topics, etc. plus 5P* INTEREST Qualifiers, as appropriate, See also: JBSF3

Use for: works that examine, or give advice about, an LGBTQIA+ person‘s process of, or journey to, recognition, personal acceptance and disclosure to others of their sexual orientation or gender identity. Use with: other subject codes and 5P* qualifiers as appropriate

Also class here: Diaspora studies. Use for: works about the study of the histories, experiences, cultures, and issues of ethnic groups or groups who share a common cultural heritage. Use with: other subject codes for interdisciplinary studies and PLACE 1* and 5PB* values from INTEREST 5* Qualifiers, as appropriate or other J* or N* codes for topics like ethnic violence or conflict, debates on multiculturalism in specific domains, such as migration, JHMC for Ethnography or Ethnology

Also class here: race relations, ethnic minorities, multiculturalism, pluriculturalism, polyethnicity. Use for: works on social and cultural topics linked to multicultural societies, or works that look at particular ethnic groups, or cultural groups. Use with: PLACE 1* and INTEREST 5P* as appropriate and with LANGUAGE 2* qualifiers for studies of groups linked by a common language, See also: JBFA
Also class here: Indigenous Studies. Use with: other subject codes for works about Indigenous peoples

Code.CodeDescription: Mixed heritage / Multiracial groups or people
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: bicultural, multicultural, mixed-race, biracial, multiracial, multiethnic groups or people

Use for: works that look at different generations, or topics, issues, problems for different generations or generational misunderstandings or conflicts, intergenerational or multigenerational topics, etc. Use all JBSP* codes with: other subject codes for works that look the generational or age groups aspects of a topic, for example JHB* for sociological approaches to topics around aging
Also class here: Childhood studies, children’s studies

Use for: works about teenagers, youths. Use with: with other subject codes for works that look at youth culture or topics that relate to young people, for example JPVH for works about Youth Rights or Rights of Young people, JBFK* for works about youth or teenage violence
Use for: works about adulthood, works that look at or are studies of adults or aspects of adulthood

Code.CodeDescription: Age groups: the elderly / old age
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: works about seniors, elders, pensioners, older retirees

Use for: works that examine hypothetical groups of people as yet unborn, works that look at Intergenerational equity for future generations. Use with: L* codes for works looking at the legal rights of future generations, or with other relevant codes looking at philosophical, religious, environmental, economic, political topics relating to future generations

Code.CodeDescription: Social groups: religious groups and communities
Code.CodeNotes: Use with: 5PG* values from INTEREST 5* Qualifiers and QR* codes as appropriate

Use for: groups associated with lifestyles that are diverse in regards to the mainstream or perceived to be outside the cultural norms, for example, counterculture movements, alternative movements, groups who are marginalised because they are perceived as not being part of the “normal”, underground movements, antiestablishment groups, Bohemian cultures and lifestyles, subcultures associated with fandoms
Also class here: freemasonry, See also: QRY* FHQ

Also class here: voluntary association or ‘elective affinities’, how and why people join and associate themselves with specific groups, such as fan clubs, fan groups, sport supporters groups, youth organisations, common interest associations, learned societies, professional associations, etc
Use all JH* codes for: textbooks or academic and specialist works. Use with: other J* codes indicating specific topics where appropriate

Use with: other subject categories for works that are about the sociology of something, sociological studies, applied sociology, or a sociological approach to a topic, when there is no more specific code for that topic, for example for military sociology use with JW* codes, for fiscal sociology use with KFFD, for rural sociology use with JBSC, for sociology of religion and belief systems use with QR*, LAQ for Sociology of law, ATF for sociology of film, JBC* for Sociology of culture, JN* codes for Sociology of Education, etc, See also: LAQ MBS
See also: GPS

Also class here: human development and family sciences. Use for: works about family structures; relationships within families, social networks, peer-groups, friendships; sociology of physical and emotional relationships with other people; social control or conformity within groups or families; co-dependency in families; works that look at how people develop physically, emotionally and socially within the context of family and society; different types of traditional and non-traditional family structures; works about found family or family of choice; extended families or kinship, works that look at different types of kinship including things like ancestors, ancestry, forebears, descents, kinship relationship, bonds of kinship, extended kinship groups or communities, structures based on kinship, See also: JBFW VFV*
Also class here: sociology of employment / unemployment, labour studies, industrial sociology

Use for: works that examine the relationships between society and death, dying and grief; how societies deal with the end of life and with death; attitudes and taboos around mortality, death and dying; customs, ceremonies and traditions around funerals, death or the dead; how societies deal with grief, bereavement and mourning and the bereaved; death literacy, See also: VFJX QRVL KNSZ

Also class here: Anthropological studies. Use with: other subject categories for works that are about the anthropology of something, when there is no more specific code for that topic, for example, with CF* for linguistic anthropology, PSXE for biological anthropology, NK* for Archaeological anthropology

Also class here: ethnography, kinship and family, Institutional anthropology, sociocultural anthropology, Culture Theory. Use with: other J* codes for different specialities in anthropology, See also: JBCC*
Use all JK* codes with: 4TM for revision and study guides, 4CP for vocational or professional qualifications, 4Z* for specific national qualifications

Code.CodeDescription: Social welfare, social policy and social services
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: human services, social care, social security policy, social care research, provision of and access to welfare, social care and healthcare, the social aspects of the policies, provision of, or access to social welfare, social care or health services, healthcare, health education

Also class here: welfare state, state or official provisions of welfare benefits, policies about welfare benefits, types of welfare benefits and systems, social policies linked to welfare, social protections
Also class here: child protection and safeguarding, social work services aimed at support of vulnerable / under-privileged youths in society, See also: LNMK
Also class here: elder abuse, maltreatment and neglect, institutions for the care of older people. Use for: social care aspect, community and government policies and associated professions or roles

Code.CodeDescription: Care of people with specific needs
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: care of people with visible or hidden disabilities, people with physical and sensory impairments, care of neurodivergent persons with additional needs. Use for: social care aspect, community and government policies and associated professions or roles. Use with: 5PM* qualifiers as appropriate

Code.CodeDescription: Care of people with mental health conditions
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: social care aspect, community and government policies and associated professions or roles. Use with: 5PM* qualifiers as appropriate, See also: MBPK VFJQ
Also class here: Volunteering, charitable giving and organisations, humanitarian, secular or religious charities, voluntary sector, civic sector or social sector

Also class here: works on international and foreign aid or assistance, humanitarian aid, secular or religious aid and relief programmes, disaster relief. Use for: domestic and international programmes, either short term or long term aid programmes, relief initiatives, emergency programmes, etc
Also class here: works on uniformed or public protective and emergency services, first responders, emergency planning, provisions of emergency and protective services, etc

Also class here: air and sea rescue services, mountain rescue, lifeboat services, paramedics, air ambulance services, specialist disaster rescue services, search and rescue services, etc. Use for: non-medical works about paramedical and equivalent emergency services, See also: MQF

Also class here: Crime studies. Use all JKV* codes with: other J* codes for different aspects of crime in the social sciences, NH* codes for historical studies, DNXC for journalistic style accounts of actual crimes, or with FF* codes for fictional accounts of particular types of crime, See also: DNXC
Also class here: surveillance, anti-terrorism measures, protection of the public from crime, policies around prevention and causes of crime, Social control theory
Also class here: Policing methods, police operations, covert operations, criminal intelligence gathering, sting operations, undercover law enforcement, investigative practices
Use with: UY or UX* for computer or digital forensic science, See also: JMK MKT
Also class here: mugging, pickpocketing, vandalism, knife crime, gun crime

Also class here: financial crimes, fraud, scams, embezzlement, bribery and corruption, cybercrimes, money laundering, counterfeiting, credit card fraud, tax evasion, bank or insurance scams, Con-men, Ponzi schemes, insider trading, copyright infringement, identity theft, forgery, call centre fraud, internet scammers, etc

Also class here: criminal gangs, mafia, bandits or banditry, modern piracy, the mob, mobsters, the Mafia, Crime syndicates, the criminal underworld, organised crime networks. Use with: J* codes for works about organised crime and specific topics, like drug or human trafficking

Also class here: violent felonies, murder, unlawful killings, torture, assault, honour crimes, rape and crimes of sexual violence, assassination, mass shootings, stabbings, robbery or extortion with violence, mob violence, looting, arson, rioting, vigilante violence, or any other crime of a violent nature. Use for: works that examine different aspects of different types of violent crime. Use with: DNXC* codes for journalistic style accounts of actual violent crimes. Use with: JBS* codes or INTEREST5* qualifiers for works about violent crimes against specific groups

Also class here: Hostages, hostage taking, missing person crimes. Use for: works that look at crimes that involve the kidnap or forceful removal of individuals or groups, or the forceful or unlawful detention of a person or persons against their will, outside official state run prisons, how these are dealt with. Use with: DNXC* for true crime accounts

Also class here: prisons, penitentiaries, penal systems and theories, restorative justice, community service, retributive justice, correctional studies, participatory justice, transformative justice, prison reform, prisoners or detainees, sentencing disparity, etc, See also: JWXR LNFX1
Also class here: Lawbreakers, outlaws, felons, crooks. Use for: works about the people who break the law or commit a crime
Also class here: Restorative justice, reintegration of ex-offenders, support for prisoners after prison, care and post-prison support, support for the formerly incarcerated, ex-felons, recidivism
Also class here: juvenile delinquency
Also class here: victim’s rights, victim-offender mediation, victim assistance, victim support, See also: DNXR

Use all JM* codes for: academic, specialist and professional level works. Use with: MKM* for Clinical psychology and psychotherapy approaches or MKL* for psychiatry. Prefer: VS* codes for practical advice for the general reader, See also: VSP*

Code.CodeDescription: Psychological theory, systems, schools and viewpoints
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: Therapies, therapeutic approaches, See also: QDTM
Also class here: psychoanalysis, Adlerian therapy, Individual psychology
Also class here: Lacanianism
Also class here: Jungian therapy
Also class here: Behavioural therapy, Behavioural psychology,
Also class here: Humanistic therapy, Person-centred therapy, Gestalt therapy, existential therapy, solution-focused therapy, transactional analysis
Also class here: the psychology, science or theory of happiness, mental well-being, psychology of positivity, psychology of having a meaningful life, See also: VSPM
Use for: works about different methods used in psychology
Also class here: psychometrics, psychological assessments
Also class here: attachment theory, psychological development, social emotional development, See also: JNC
Also class here: Psychosocial risk factors or hazards, psychosocial health. Use for: works that look at the interaction of mental health, social health, emotional health and spiritual wellbeing

Also class here: Family therapy, couples therapy, relationship therapy. Use for : works that look at psychology that is focused on the emotions, thoughts, and behaviour of individuals, couples, and families in relationships and in the broader environment in which they function

Also class here: works that look at gender dysphoria, gender incongruence, works that look at psychological aspects or topics related to gender or gender identity. Use for: studies of the social, cultural, behavioural, and psychological factors that are associated with being male, female, or other gender identities, or works that explore the relationship between gender identity and gender expression, or look at the role of gender in shaping a persons behaviours, feelings or ways of thinking
Also class here: Social identity
Also class here: psychology of communication, both verbal and non-verbal, body language, See also: GTC

Also class here: Industrial and organizational psychology, I-O psychology, psychology of work lives, psychological approaches to understand and optimize the effectiveness, health, and well-being of both organizations and individuals in a work or professional environment, See also: SCGP KNXC
Also class here: psychological profiling, See also: JKV*
See also: PSAN5

Also class here: Counselling psychology, media psychology, environmental psychology, traffic psychology, political psychology. Use for: works about the use of psychological methods and findings of scientific psychology to solve practical problems of human behaviour and experience. Use with: other codes for area of application
See also: MKM*
Also class here: affective neuroscience

Also class here: cognitive neuroscience, psychological works on learning, cognitive processes, such as memory and memory loss, intelligence, reasoning, perception, language, metacognition, cognitive control, working memory, long-term memory, Cognitive therapies

Code.CodeDescription: Psychology: the self, ego, identity, personality
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: Personality psychology, Personality theories, personality types, personality traits, extraversion and introversion, conscientiousness, agreeableness, neuroticism, openness to experience, development of personality. Use for: works that study personality and all its variations in individuals
Also class here: psychological works on conscious and unconscious mind; sleep and dreams; altered states of mind, hypnosis, drug-induced, etc, See also: VXN
See also: VFVC JBFW
Also class here: parapsychology. Use for: specialist (professional and academic) works or studies. Prefer: VX* categories for more popular, general works, See also: VXP

Also class here: Education studies. Use all JN* codes for: works about education as a practice or subject. Use with: GP* codes for different types of research in education. Prefer: YP* codes for schoolbooks or educational material for pupils in pre-tertiary education, See also: GP* YP*

Also class here: educational philosophies, educational perennialism, educational essentialism, critical pedagogy, democratic education, critical thinking in education, learning styles theories, non-formal and informal learning theories, etc

Code.CodeDescription: Moral and social purpose of education
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: works supporting the theories behind education focussed particularly on themes connected to society and behaviour in it

Also class here: Montessori education, Waldorf or Steiner education. Use for: works about the theory or principles of pedagogical theories labelled as progressive, in comparison to more traditional curricula and theories. Use with: other JN* codes as appropriate
Also class here: history of specific schools, colleges, as well as general history

Also class here: Educational psychology, works for educational psychologists, scientific study of human learning and learning processes, works about the psychological problems that can arise during teaching and training

Also class here: formal education, informal or non-formal education. Use for: general works about the systems or structures of education, comparative education, different types of educational systems or structures. Use with: GP* codes for different types of research

Use with: other JN* codes and PLACE 1* Qualifiers for comparisons between different education systems or comparative education studies, GP* codes for different types of research in comparative education
Also class here: testing, evaluations, measuring students
Use for: works about social pedagogy as a field of study

Also class here: government, regional, local educational teaching or learning strategies and policies, educational reforms, communication strategies for educational institutions, school policies, policies on admissions, selection, catchment areas, international education strategies, etc

Also class here: pastoral care, student affairs, student life, student welfare issues, absence, truancy, discipline, safety and security of students and in educational establishments, child protection in schools, emergency drills and practices, crisis management, academic development advice, welfare of exchange or international students, student exchange programs, school wellbeing strategies, relations and communication with parents or carers, pupil and student safeguarding, school safety etc

Also class here: works about diversity, inclusivity, equity, equality, accessibility, social mobility in education; or works that look at exclusion or those excluded from education; or works about access to education for the disadvantaged, or low-income groups, migrants, strategies to deal with prejudices and discrimination, equal access to education for girls and women, training for all educational personnel in inclusivity, support and resources for school leadership for inclusive education, works that identify barriers to education and policies for removing these. Use for: both formulating policy and practical applications. Use with: 5YS-UN-D as appropriate

Code.CodeDescription: Education: relations with parents, communities or organisations
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: Parent, carer and home participation in student or pupil education and development, relations and communications between schools or teachers and parents, carers or legal guardians, parental or carer volunteering and in-school activities, help with learning at home, teachers and schools involving parents in supporting their children’s academic learning, school-home and home-school communication, joint decision-making, schools helping parents or carer get children prepared for entering school. Use for: works about schools and community relations, engagement and outreach with communities, strategies and policies for dealing with hostility or pressure from external individuals and bodies or communities on educational institutions, the role of educational institutions in their communities, collaborating with the community, how educational institutions deal with external bodies, funding bodies, government or state bodies, private corporations etc
Use for: works aimed at professionals dealing with childcare or general works on subject, See also: JNLA
Also class here: elective home education, unschooling, worldschooling. Use for: works about forms of education for school aged children either at home or other places other than a school

Also class here: school governance, boards of education, head teachers, superintendents, principals or other leadership or administrative roles, or general works about the administration or organizations in educational institutions, parent-teacher associations or organizations, non-teaching and support staff, management of education and educational institutions

Code.CodeDescription: Funding of education and student finance

Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: teachers, teaching assistants, educator roles, professors, classroom assistants, instructors, working conditions and practices for teaching staff, policies and strategies for safety, wellbeing and welfare of staff, anti-bullying and harassment policies,
See also: VSK
Also class here: elementary, preparatory, infant and junior schools
Also class here: senior and high schools

Also class here: Charter schools, Academy trusts, Private schools. Use for: schools that receives government funding but that operate independently of the established state school system or schools that not administered or funded by government, but are financed by fees or private sector funds
Also class here: boarding schools, seminaries, military schools or academies, residential schools or any educational institutions that also have pupils living and staying in the educational faculty
Also class here: adventure education, outdoor learning, forest schools. Use for: organized learning that takes place in the outdoors
Also class here: all advanced and post-secondary education, including institutions offering vocational, technical or non-degree courses as well as universities, See also: VSK
Also class here: professional development of educators, continuous learning, in-service training

Also class here: lifelong learning, popular education, community education, ‘Bildung’. Use for: works about education or training of adult learners that are neither university nor vocational training, See also: VSL VSN
Also class here: online learning, remote or blended learning

Use for: works on industrial / vocational training, professional development and education as a subject. Prefer: YPW* or other subjects codes, such as T*, and the appropriate 4CP* Qualifiers for teaching material and coursework for teaching vocational subjects, See also: YPW* T* 4CP*

Code.CodeDescription: Teaching of students with different educational needs
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: special education, mixed classes of students with different cultural or linguistic backgrounds, mixed classes with pupils from different socioeconomic backgrounds, techniques and advice for teaching different types of group, communication and learning techniques, etc. Use all JNS* codes with: 5P* Qualifiers for works about teaching to specific groups with specific or special needs

Code.CodeDescription: Teaching of students with physical impairments or disabilities
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: teaching of students with impaired hearing or vision, or any physical condition giving rise to specific educational needs. Use with: 5PM* codes as appropriate

Code.CodeDescription: Teaching of students with learning difficulties or disorders

Use all JNU* codes for: works that are about how an educator can teach a specific subject. Also class here: interactive resources, teachers’ editions of textbooks, learning materials and teaching aids etc. Use with: the code for the subject taught, for example, YP* for teachers materials for use at primary or secondary school level, or with other subject codes if the work is teachers material for teaching adults, and use with 4*EDUCATIONAL PURPOSE Qualifiers to indicate level as appropriate and JNUM should be designated as the Main Subject code
Use with: the code for the subject taught, using YP* Educational codes where appropriate

Code.CodeDescription: Educational equipment and technology, computer-aided learning (CAL)

Use for: works on different parts of the political spectrum, or political ideologies or movements that do not have more precise codes.
