Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: Addition, subtraction, multiplication, division
Also class here: the earth sciences, natural sciences, life sciences, combined sciences
Also class here: geology, geoscience, geomorphology, oceanography, physical geography, ecology, glaciology, climatology, meteorology
Also class here: Educational: product design

Also class here: Educational: vehicle engineering and technology. Use for: Engineering courses taught at secondary level. NB: YPMT3 may be used with T* codes for more specialised engineering material but the YPMT3 code MUST always be the Main subject to indicate it is educational material for young people
Also class here: Educational: nutrition, food preparation and cookery, food safety, See also: YPWC4
Also class here: Educational: electronic products, systems and technology, electricity
Also class here: digital competencies or skills, coding or programming classes, information and communication technology, computer studies, digital citizenship

Use for: material aimed at pupils in primary or secondary education. Use with: appropriate EDUCATIONAL PURPOSE 4* qualifiers. NB: YPW* codes may be used with T* or other codes for more specialised vocational material but the YPW* code MUST always be the Main subject to indicate it is educational material for young people

Code.CodeDescription: Educational: Family and consumer sciences / domestic management
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: material for pupils that deal with the economics and management of the home, the family and relationships with the wider community

Code.CodeDescription: Educational: Other vocational education and training
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: all vocational subjects taught at secondary level schools not listed separately. Use with: appropriate EDUCATIONAL PURPOSE 4* qualifiers. NB: YPWC* codes may be used with T* or other codes for more specialised vocational material but the YPWC* code MUST always be the Main subject to indicate it is educational material for young people
Use for: material for pupils about professions linked to adult health and social care
Use for: material for pupils about professions linked to child care
Use for: material for pupils about sales / retail sector

Code.CodeDescription: Educational: Hospitality, catering, leisure and tourism
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: material for pupils about the leisure industry, travel, tourism, hotels, food and drinks service, See also: YPMT4

Code.CodeDescription: Educational: Hairdressing, salon and beauty therapy skills
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: material for pupils about cosmetology, skin care, haircare, barbering, art of makeup, spa skills and other education specialities linked to beauty treatment or personal grooming, See also: TTVH
Use for: material for pupils about the world of work, the skills needed, placements

Code.CodeDescription: Educational: Construction, building and related skills
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: Built Environment, Building Engineering. Use for: material for pupils about topics in the construction and related sectors. NB: YPWD codes may be used with TN* codes for more specialised vocational material but the YPWD code MUST always be the Main subject to indicate it is educational material for young people, See also: TNT

Code.CodeDescription: Educational: Agriculture, horticulture and related subjects
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: fishing, forestry, animal care and management, arboriculture, countryside management, blacksmithing, etc. Use for: material for pupils about topics in the rural or land-based sectors. NB: YPWE codes may be used with TV* codes for more specialised vocational material but the YPWE code MUST always be the Main subject to indicate it is educational material for young people
Also class here: Sports studies, gym class, physical training (PT). Use for: material for pupils related to maintaining the human body through physical exercises and sports

Code.CodeDescription: Educational: Transport, logistics and related skills
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: distribution, driving skills. Use for: material for pupils about topics in these sectors. NB: YPWG codes may be used with T* or K* codes for more specialised vocational material but the YPWG code MUST always be the Main subject to indicate it is educational material for young people, See also: TR*

Code.CodeDescription: Educational: General studies, educational skills and competencies
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: educational material that takes a multi-disciplinary approach to the world the student lives in or teaches pupils general skills or competencies
Use for: educational material that gives a broad sweep of general knowledge or culture or teaches cultural awareness and expression

Use for: general material that teaches skills needed for studying or learning efficiently, such as functional skills, learning techniques, organizational skills, writing techniques, note taking, research skills, library skills, etc

Code.CodeDescription: Educational: Memory skills and creative thinking
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: general material that teaches pupils thinking skills, including initiative
Use for: general material that teaches pupils skills for interaction with others or dealing with daily life

Code.CodeDescription: Educational: Uniformed public or protective services
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: material aimed at pupils preparing for one of the uniformed public or protective services, such as the fire service, paramedics, police or armed services. NB: YPWN codes may be used with JKSW* or JWC* codes for more specialised vocational material but the YPWN code MUST always be the Main subject to indicate it is educational material for young people

Use for: ALL study and revision guides or supplementary workbook / exercise books for primary and secondary education, notes or resumes of texts or subjects meant to help students study or revise a particular aspect of a subject or a specific work. Use with: relevant YP* code above indicating subject where possible

Use for: instructional study material or activity books, meant to complement formal educational structures, usually designed for learning during the long holiday between educational years or grades, usually meant to revise topics already learnt and prepare for the transition to the next educational year or grade, and often presented in a fun, activity based format. Use with: EDUCATIONAL 4* qualifiers to indicate levels, plus use with other YP* codes for particular subjects or just YPZH if it covers all the main subjects covered in an academic year

Use for: material about problem solving using pictures and diagrams, or material aimed at improving the ability to understand and analyse visual information and solve problems, such as, identifying relationships, similarities and differences between shapes and patterns, recognizing visual sequences and relationships between objects, and remembering these

Use for: material about problem solving using words and letters, or material aimed at improving understanding, thinking or reasoning using concepts framed in words, or material that helps evaluate the ability to think constructively, rather than just simple fluency or vocabulary recognition
Use with: other Y* codes to indicate subject of reference material

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage reference: Dictionaries and Languages
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: monolingual dictionaries for school or home use, other language reference works and titles about languages and language skills, word lists, vocabulary, grammar, usage guides, etc. Use all YRD* codes with: LANGUAGE 2* Qualifiers, as appropriate. Prefer: YPC* codes for materials for use in a formal educational structure, See also: YPC*

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage reference: Bilingual / multilingual dictionaries
Children’s / Teenage reference: Non-native or second language study and reference
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: self-study or home language learning materials, word or vocabulary books etc. Use for: any titles, independent of format, aimed at helping young people learn or improve non-maternal language skills

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage reference: Encyclopaedias, general reference
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: non-subject-specific works only; for subject-specific reference works, use YRG
Also class here: subject specific dictionaries / glossaries. Use with: another Y* code indicating the subject or scope of the reference work, YP* codes for material designed for education

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage reference: Atlases and maps
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: collections of maps for children, atlases that present different topics for children. Use with: other Y* codes as appropriate and with: PLACE 1* Qualifiers, as appropriate

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage: Personal and social topics
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: problems, issues, debates or challenges for youth or young people, situations and skills associated with these topics. Use all YX* codes: for titles dealing with any of these subjects either as non-fiction, factual approach or through stories or narratives. Use all YX* codes with: appropriate YF* code for fiction, stories or narratives where the main themes are personal or social topics, or with other Y* or XQ* codes to give greater detail for works dealing with these topics or issues through other subjects, with 5* INTEREST qualifiers when topics applies to particular interests. NB: YX may be used with J* or VF* codes to indicate there is no specific Y* code or qualifier but if mixing YX codes with J* or VF* codes, the YX code or another Y* code must be designated as the Main Subject and sent with a 5A* qualifier

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Body and health
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: advice for sleeping well, brushing teeth, dental and mouth hygiene, visiting the dentist, looking after the body, hygiene topics. Use for: popular health approaches to looking after the body, health and well-being. Use with: YXL* codes for mental health topics linked to the body and health

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Fitness, exercise and healthy eating
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: personal health and hygiene, taking care of teeth, looking after your body, being active, food and health, nutrition and diet, topics around weight, veganism, vegetarianism, workouts and fitness routines for young people

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Yoga, meditation, mindfulness
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: works about yoga or related practical techniques for mental and physical health and well-being for young people

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Hair and hair care
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: taking care of hair, brushing hair, titles about loving your hair, hair loss, alopecia, hairdos and hairstyles, etc

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Sex education and the facts of life
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: works that discuss or explain to young people aspects of sex and sexuality advice including, but not limited to, maturing, consent, sexual relationships, physical intimacy, sexual health, sexual attraction, sexuality and social media, sexual boundaries, talking about sex, contraception, birth control, dealing with sexual pressure, where do babies come from, pregnancy, etc

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: puberty
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: works that explain puberty and the changes to the body, periods, menstruation, the menstrual cycle, changes to moods, hormonal changes, etc

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: LGBTQIA+
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: works that discuss or explain to young people aspects of LGBTQIA+ or queer life, culture, identities, history, events, health, wellbeing, sexuality, relationships, biographies, stories, dealing with prejudice, discrimination or any of the multiple aspects of LGBTQIA+ life. Use with: 5PSG, 5PSL, 5PT, 5PU, 5PV, 5PW or other 5* INTEREST Qualifiers as appropriate or YF* codes for stories that are about these topics, any YN* or other YX* codes for general interest or non-fiction works, for example, YXA* for works about health or body, YNH for LGBTQIA+ history, YNB for biographies, YXQ* for works about violence or abuse based on LGBTQIA+ identity, etc

Use for: works that tell stories of, examine or give advice to young people about LGBTQIA+ person‘s process of, or journey to, recognition, personal acceptance and disclosure to others of their sexual orientation or gender identity. Use with: other subject codes and 5P* INTEREST Qualifiers as appropriate

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Gender identity
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: titles that deal with anything to do with gender for young people, for example what it means to be a girl or boy or questions about identity. Use with: other codes as appropriate to give more information, See also: YNMF YNMH

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Self-awareness and self-esteem
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: topics and advice about self-discovery, self-knowledge, self-worth, self-image, self-identity, self-reliance, building confidence

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Emotions, moods, feelings and behaviours
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: general titles about emotions or titles that deal with multiple emotions. Use all YXE* codes for: titles that deal with several or various emotions, what they are, how to recognise them, how to deal with them, or understand them, express them, or encourage them
Also class here: coping with anger, disgust, hostility, jealousy, selfishness, feeling grumpy, tantrums, bad temper or mood, rage

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage emotions: Sadness, unhappiness, disappointment
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: gloominess, emotional pain or suffering
Also class here: feeling worried or anxious, dealing with worries, distress, uncertainty, stress, fear, separation anxiety, shame, embarrassment
Also class here: feeling like an outsider or a loner, feeling alone or lonely, feeling alienated

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage emotions: Compassion, empathy, kindness
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: accepting differences, solidarity with or compassion for others, courtesy, generosity, tolerance, love and understanding

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage emotions: Courage, bravery, hope
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: heroism, perseverance, persistence, loyalty, trust, honesty
Also class here: pleasure, cheerfulness, contentment, gladness, delight, excitement, optimism, gratitude, thankfulness, optimism, mirth, elation, or just being happy

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage emotions: Mischief and mischievous behaviour
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: Being naughty, misbehaving, prankish, teasing, getting into trouble. Use for: works about causing or showing a fondness for causing trouble in a playful way, works that show the consequences of misbehaviour, or works where being naughty is a key theme

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Families and family members
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: aunts, uncles, cousins, family life, multigenerational families, kinship groups, relatives, blended families, extended family members, stepfamilies or any type of family etc. Use for: works about families, issues in families, particular members of a family, etc. Use with: 5PHA* qualifiers

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Parents
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: mothers, fathers, single-parents, step-parents

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Grandparents
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: Grandmothers, grandfathers, grandparents and their grandchildren

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Divorce, separation, family break-up
Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Adoption / fostering
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: orphans

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Siblings
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: brothers, sisters, step and half brothers and sisters

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: New baby
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: new brother, new sister, new sibling, or titles about babies

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Death and grief
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: loss, dying, bereavement, mourning, works explaining death, how and why people die, end of life, etc

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Suicide
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: getting help or dealing with suicidal ideation or thoughts, helping understand when someone commits suicide, suicide prevention, advice for talking about suicide. Use with: 5JB for material specifically created for or aimed at young men or boys, 5JA for material specifically created for or aimed at young women or girls, 5PS*, 5PT for works aimed at LGBTQIA+ youth, or other 5P* qualifiers for works relating to specific groups, or 5L* for works about specific age groups, for example, 5LFE for works about older teenagers, 5PHA* codes when discussing family members, etc

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Relationships (non-family / groups)
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: relationships within peer or social groups, interpersonal relationships, frenemies, cliques, gangs, learning about relationships, skills for interaction with others outside families and other relationship topics, relationships with adults from a young persons perspective, dealing with the adult world, etc

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Friends and friendships
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: making new friends, friendship groups, found family, issues around relationships with friends, such as conformity, popularity or isolation within a group of friends, end of friendships, advice about making friends, etc, See also: YFM

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Dating, relationships, romance and love
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: topics like first attraction, being in a couple, advice about romantic relationships, dating for the first time, first love, unrequited love, also advice about boundaries, consent and intimacy in a romantic relationship, kissing, advice for breaking up, ending a relationship, problems in relationships

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Life skills and choices
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: manners, behaviour, dilemmas, consequences, responsibilities, skills for interacting with modern life, other people, following or not following rules, getting into trouble, taking responsibility for actions, assuming the consequences, not using violence, not hitting, kicking or biting, etc

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Teenage pregnancy
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: teenage parenthood, teenage mums and dads. Use for: works aimed at young people explaining pregnancy, birth, parenthood or topics around being a young mother or father

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Drugs and addiction
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: topics around substance addiction, alcohol abuse, etc

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Disability, impairments and special needs
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: physical disabilities and impairments, visible or invisible disabilities or conditions, wheelchair users, etc. Use with: 5PM* Qualifiers as appropriate

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Physical and mental health conditions
Code.CodeNotes: Use all YXL* codes for: titles aimed either at young people who have a particular condition or to help understand others who have a particular condition. Use all YXL* codes with: 5PM* Qualifiers as appropriate. NB: YXL* codes may be used with V* codes when there is no specific Y* code or qualifier but if mixing YXL* codes with V* codes, the YXL* code or another Y* code must be designated as the Main Subject and sent with a 5A* qualifier

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Illness and specific physical health conditions
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: living with disease and long-term physical conditions, injuries, first aid, medicine, titles that explain specific illnesses, diseases, etc to young people. Use with: YNH for history of medicine, plagues and disease in the past, histories of pandemics and epidemics, etc

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Cancer
Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Mental health and mental wellbeing
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: mental disorders, trauma and traumatic experiences. Use for: works that help children or teenagers deal with mental health, personal trauma or traumatic events around them, how to process or talk about trauma, with adverse childhood experiences, advice about good mental health and wellbeing

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Eating disorders and body image
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: ARFID, anorexia, bulimia, binge eating, body dysmorphia, purging disorder, disordered eating, advice about body acceptance, body positivity, body neutrality

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Anxiety, depression and self-harm
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: panic attacks, severe stress

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Positive / good mental health
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: positive self-image, well-being. Use for: works that explain, help or give advice about good mental health and wellness, about judging life positively and feeling good, positive wellbeing, positive images

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Multicultural
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: works on social and cultural topics linked to multiculturalism, pluriculturalism, biculturalism and multicultural, pluricultural or bicultural societies

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Racism and anti-racism
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: xenophobia, race relations. Use for: works about discrimination and prejudice based on skin colour, race or ethnic origin, or prejudices based on the perception that someone is foreign or from outside the community, and issues of inequality and discrimination, as well as measures to address racism. Use with: YNH for historical topics, See also: JBFA1

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Diversity, equality, equity and inclusion
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: books that deal with these topics and stories with a particularly diverse cast of characters, or which illustrate accessibility, social justice, equity, diversity, or inclusivity (DEI) within the context of the story without necessarily being the subject of the story. Use with: YF* codes for stories and values from 5P* INTEREST Qualifiers as appropriate

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Prejudice and intolerance
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: discrimination, injustice, the judgements of others. Use with: YNH for historical topics

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Bullying, violence, abuse and peer pressure
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: use of violent or abusive language. Use for: works that explore these topics, often titles aimed at explaining or helping young people understand or deal with these topics. Use with: YF* when it is the major element of the story

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Abuse / exploitation
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: physical, mental, emotional or sexual abuse, coercive control, domestic abuse, or works aimed at young people about criminal exploitation, debt bondage, exploitation of vulnerable children by criminal gangs

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Bullying and harassment
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: online trolling and bullying, coercion, cyberbullying, cyberstalking, physical or verbal bullying or harassment, relational bullying, collective bullying or mobbing, bullies and accomplices, victims of bullying, effects of bullying and harassment, bystander effect, school bullying, victimisation

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Violence
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: Knife violence, gun violence, bombs, violent acts, acts of terrorism, kidnapping, violent threats, violent rampages. Use for: works aimed at young people dealing with physical violence or conflict involving weapons, helping young people deal with knife crime, with gun violence, stabbings, shootings, violent gang crimes, school shootings, violence of war, for works helping young people avoid violence, or deal with the trauma of weapons related violence

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Personal safety
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: dealing with strangers, road safety, safety in the home etc. Use with: YXZE for titles about personal safety in the event of an emergency

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Runaways
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: fugitives, escapees. Use for: works that look at young people that run away and reasons around this, running away from home, or family or school or escaping things like repression, slavery, conflict, etc. Use with: YF* codes for stories about runaways, with YNB for biographies of runaways, or YNH for historical approaches, See also: YXZM

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: School, education and teachers
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: works that explore topics like starting school, attending school, going to a new school, school life, education topics, titles about teachers and educators, school librarians

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Truancy and school problems
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: works about issues at school, around repeated absence, non-attendance, avoiding school, etc

Code.CodeDescription: Teenage personal and social topics: Advice on careers and further education, leaving school
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: titles about work, jobs, careers, professions aimed at a young audience but not educational, See also: YPJV2 YPWC9

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: First / new experiences and life changes
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: Dealing with and understanding change, talking about change, changes or new experiences like moving home, living in a new town, starting a new school, making new friends, a new family, new siblings, etc. Use for: titles that explore or deal with major or significant new experiences or change in the life or world of a young person, how to deal or cope with this experience or change, or explains about these experiences or changes, from the perspective of the child or teenager etc. Use with: other Y* codes or qualifiers to give more details of the main theme or experience

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage personal and social topics: Growing up / coming of age
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: titles that deal with the changes from childhood or youth to adulthood, such as taking on adult responsibilities, career choices, character growth, gaining independence, self-reliance, moving away from home, going to university, first experience of love, etc. Use with: YF* for coming of age fiction, YXA* codes for works about changes to the body, or sex, YXHL for first love, etc

Also class here: social activism, general works on social justice. Use for: titles that deal directly with the topics or explain debates around social issues for young people. Use with: other YX* codes to give greater detail; YF* fiction codes for stories that are about these topics. NB: YXZ may be used with JBF* codes if there are no more precise Y* codes but if mixing YXZ with JBF* codes, a Y* code MUST be designated as the Main Subject and sent with a 5A* qualifier

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage social topics: Activism / activists
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: titles about social activism, environmental activism, human rights, social or civil rights movements, causes and other forms of engagement as activists by young people, volunteering or volunteer engagement. Use with: other YN* or YX* codes to give greater detail and with YNB for biographies of activists

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage social topics: Identity / belonging
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: titles that explore topics or themes around notions of identity and belonging, as individuals or as part of a particular group or communities, identity or belonging based on relationship to a place, based on a shared culture or heritage or other works that explore the notion of identity or belonging for children or teenagers

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage social topics: Peace / reconciliation
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: works for young people about peace after conflict, maintaining peace, ideas for creating, keeping, spreading peace and peaceful actions, resolving conflict, themes and topics around reconciliation between different groups or persons

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage social topics: Accidents, disasters or emergencies
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: either works about the impact or consequences, on both people and society, of both natural and human-made disasters and accidents; things such as diseases, plagues, epidemics, pandemics, famine, malnutrition, volcanic explosions, earthquakes, extreme-weather, floods, forced movement of peoples as a result of disasters; or works about accidents like fires, crashes, shipwrecks, maritime and air disasters or accidents, rail or road accidents, explosions, oil spills, getting trapped or lost, etc; or for titles that explain how to prepare for disasters, emergencies, etc for example, what to do during an earthquake, or major fire or tsunami

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage social topics: Fame, celebrity, fandom
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: works for young people about fame, celebrity, being famous, the search for fame and the issues with being famous or a celebrity, being an idol, being glamorous or wealthy, or works about being a fan or fandom

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage social topics: Environment, sustainability and green issues
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: looking after our planet, climate change, pollution, rubbish, plastics, recycling, climate emergency, climate strikes, environmental champions, looking after our future, protecting nature, conservation, water use and conservation, managing natural resources, sustainable solutions, reducing consumption and use of resources. Use for: works that look at these topics and also ones that have ideas for solutions, or what young people can do themselves

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage: Social topics: Poverty / precarity
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: works that look at social issues topics in society around social instability, deprivation and hardship, homelessness, the unhoused, hunger, economically disadvantaged, food poverty, etc

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage social topics: Migration / refugees
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: asylum seekers, immigrants and immigration, emigrants and emigration, displacement, exile, forced journeys or relocation, diasporas. Use with: YNH for history titles or YNB for biographies, YF* for stories and INTEREST 5P* qualifiers as appropriate

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage social topics: Religious issues / debates
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: titles that look at discussions, debates, topics, controversies, or other issues related to religion, belief, faith, religious identity, etc. Use with: YNR* or other Y* codes and 5PG* INTEREST qualifiers as appropriate

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage social topics: War and conflict issues
Children’s / Teenage stationery and miscellaneous items
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: Book accessories, gift items and merchandise, non-book products in the book supply chain or identifying a non-book product that has no particular theme or topic and is clearly content free but still needs to be classified as something. Use all YZ* codes for: products such as stationery and non-book articles for children or adolescents that would not be categorised using another Y* subject category as a primary or main subject. Use with: other subject codes as appropriate but YZ* should be the main or principal code. NB: more details of the type non-book product should be sent in other metadata

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage: Gift and novelty books / items
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: novelty products or books, typically small format and of a decorative, humorous or inspirational nature, often intended to be given as one-off gifts to children or teenagers or for novelty products that do NOT easily fit into other sections and are often displayed at point of sale. DO NOT USE: for marketing purposes indicating a title would make a good gift, (all books make good gifts!)

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage: Miscellaneous non-book items: Games, puzzles or toys
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: Board games, travel-games, strategy games, jigsaw puzzles, 3-D puzzles classic games, family games, card games, educational games and toys, book related toys, figurines and action figures, soft toys, etc. Use for: any type of non-book game or puzzle sold separately from books. Use with: other codes to indicate the subject or theme of the game or puzzle. NB: Details of formats and types of games are conveyed in other product metadata

Also class here: any printed stationery item, posters, kits, postcard packs, bookmarks, etc intended for children or teenagers. Use with: another code indicating subject where possible., See also: WZS

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage: Printed stationery items: Calendars / diaries
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: printed agendas, annual planners, academic year diaries and planners. Use with: other codes to indicate the subject or theme of the calendar or diary. NB: Details of formats and types of calendars or diaries are conveyed in other product metadata

Code.CodeDescription: Children’s / Teenage stationery items: Thematic and guided journals and notebooks
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: creative journals, planners, journals or albums to record information about special events. Use for: journals that you fill in, which have some pre-printed text or images to inspire what to write or note down, or entries with a prompt or prompts to write about a particular aspect of your life, but are not linked to a particular year. Use with: another secondary code indicating a subject as appropriate, and 5H* qualifiers if for an event
Also class here: blank exercise books, autograph books, scrapbooks and other content-free items for children or teenagers, See also: WZSN

Use PLACE 1* Qualifier codes WITH appropriate subject codes for: indicating the geographical scope and applicability of the content, such as the location of a travel guide, the setting of a novel, the jurisdiction to which laws apply, the history of a particular place, the peoples, arts, traditions, or culture of a particular geographical location, etc. Where options exist, e.g. terms representing actual, historical, cultural, administrative, or geophysical entities, use the expression that best suits the content. Where no code exists for a specific location, use the nearest most appropriate broader code that includes it. DO NOT USE: to indicate any geographical aspect that is not to do with the content or subject of a book (e.g. place of publication, market availability, nationality of author – this is described in other metadata, etc). National extensions (i.e. 1*-xx- format codes, where ‘xx’ indicates a country code) can be assigned by any user, and are not exclusive to users in the indicated country. This section is not intended as an exhaustive gazetteer of all places but a list of commonly used locations in the global book supply chain. Use TIME PERIOD 3* Qualifier codes WITH appropriate subject codes for: indicating the time period range of a works content, such as the period covered by an art book (A*), a history book (N*), a memoir or biography (DN*), historical fiction (FV*), a Children’s history book (YNH*), etc. National extensions (i.e. 3*-xx- format codes, where ‘xx’ indicates a country code) are for specific named periods of time that are important in particular markets but do not necessarily fit neatly into the structure of the general TIME PERIOD qualifiers. All national extensions are sub-categories of a core time period code, so can be mapped back to a standard period. National extensions can be assigned by any user, and are not exclusive to users in the indicated country. TIME PERIOD qualifiers are usually used in conjunction with PLACE 1* qualifiers. (Specific historical events or individual years would be conveyed in detail elsewhere in a products metadata, for example by the title, the table of contents, the descriptive text or keywords). DO NOT USE: for indicating the year of an annual or road atlas or travel guide or the year a work was originally published in, (this is described in other metadata). Use INTEREST 5* Qualifier codes WITH appropriate subject codes for: indicating a variety of characteristics relating to the main content of the particular work. 5A* age codes to qualify Y* codes, 5H* to indicate content about a particular holiday or event, 5L* to indicate content about a particular age group / generation, 5P* to indicate content about a particular grouping of people, etc. National extensions (i.e. 5*-xx- format codes, where ‘xx’ indicates a country code) can be assigned by any user, and are not exclusive to users in the indicated country. All 5* codes must be used to describe a main content or topic of the work. DO NOT USE: as a marketing target audience code, the 5* Qualifier must relate to the main content of a work. DO NOT USE: code “5” itself, but select appropriate specific qualifiers from section 5*

Code.CodeDescription: Interest age / level (Content adapted or suitable for this age and above)
Code.CodeNotes: Use all 5A* age codes for: defining the Y* or X* codes – 5A* age numbers are used instead of named codes, such as juvenile, middle grade, young adult, as these have different meanings in different countries or languages. Select one 5A* code indicating a general guideline starting or base interest age of the content in any works aimed primarily at children or teenagers. All Y* codes (except YP* which use 4* codes) MUST be accompanied by one 5A* qualifier code to give guidance of interest age, for example: book content for an audience of 9 to 12 age group, should use 5AK, as the lower age; content of interest to teenagers should use 5AP or 5AQ; content for older teenagers and young adults should use 5AS, 5AT or 5AU as appropriate. 5AR, 5AX and 5AZ can be used with any relevant subject code. All 5A* codes can be used with X* subject codes if the Comic book is aimed at children or teenagers. DO NOT USE: 5A itself – always use 5A* codes. NB: Greater detail of age range, reading age, interest age etc would be communicated in other metadata

Code.CodeDescription: Content adapted or suitable for reluctant or struggling readers (children / teenagers)
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: High-low readers, Hi-Lo content aimed at children or teenagers. Use for: books that are specially written for or considered suitable for young people who do not want to read, have difficulty reading, or are struggling to read. Usually these books will have a higher interest age and a lower reading age. Content is usually aimed at a particular interest age but the language used is purposefully slightly simpler than most average content aimed at the same interest age in that language, so that it is easier to read or listen to than other titles. These are often titles in specific named collections and will often have notions of levels of difficulty associated with them by the publisher and / or may be accompanied by indications of complexity. Use with: one other 5A* Interest age qualifier. Prefer: 5AX for reluctant adult readers or 5AZ for accessible content and 4L codes for second language titles, See also: 5AX 5AZ 4L*

Code.CodeDescription: Interest age: from c 17 years to c 29 years
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: works aimed specifically at older teens and young adults in their 20s, those who are newly adult, emerging adulthood. This age group may be referred to in some places as young adults or sometimes as new adults. The content is specifically created for and about this group but can also appeal to other groups as well. Prefer: 5LKE for titles about this age group. DO NOT USE: with Y* codes, See also: 5LKE

Code.CodeDescription: Content adapted or suitable for adult emergent / reluctant readers
Code.CodeNotes: Also class here: High-low readers, Hi-Lo content aimed at adults. Use for: books that are specifically aimed at adult literacy or helping adult readers with reading difficulties or books that are suitable for adult readers who are not confident in their reading abilities or suitable for the newly literate. Content is aimed at adult interests but the language used is purposefully slightly simpler than most average content aimed at adults so that it is easier to read or listen to than other titles

Code.CodeDescription: Content adapted or suitable for people with learning / communication difficulties or impairments
Code.CodeNotes: Use for: indicating works where the content is specifically adapted for, or purposefully written for, or aimed at people, regardless of age, with special or additional needs, who may have difficulty in accessing or reading the content of most titles. This could include content specifically adapted for people with, for example, dyslexia and other reading or learning disabilities, cognitive impairments or disorders, memory disorders, dementia or Alzheimer’s, visual or other sensory impairments, profound and multiple learning disabilities, etc. Use with: 5PM* Qualifiers as appropriate

Use all 5H* codes for: indicating that the content of a work is largely about or relates to the holiday, event or season, for example a book featuring a Christmas story would use 5HPD or a book about birthdays for children would use 5HKA, a romance story that is all about summer could use 5HRB. DO NOT USE: to create list of suggested titles for sale at a particular season (this is information that is conveyed elsewhere in the supply chain) if those titles do not have content relating to the 5H* code

Use for: content that is about public or civic holidays or celebrations in general or about a holiday or celebration that does not have a more precise code. Use with: 1* PLACE qualifiers when associated with a particular area

Also class here: Solar New Year festivals and ceremonies. Use for: titles about New Year traditions and celebrations from different calendars, cultures and regions.
